26
00:02:27,848 --> 00:02:29,848
(Burns) Mexicans, right over the hill!

27
00:02:29,950 --> 00:02:31,650
(Fincham) Mexicans back yonder!

28
00:02:31,752 --> 00:02:33,518
- Close the gate!
- Right behind us!

29
00:02:33,620 --> 00:02:35,754
(Burns) Urrea's whole army back yonder!

30
00:02:35,856 --> 00:02:38,256
Close the damned gate!
Close the damned gate!

31
00:02:38,359 --> 00:02:40,559
(Fincham) General Urrea's
army right over the hill!

32
00:02:40,644 --> 00:02:42,260
(Samuel Wallace) Whoa, our scouts

33
00:02:42,363 --> 00:02:44,613
said Urrea's army wasn't
due for a few days, boys.

34
00:02:44,732 --> 00:02:46,765
(Burns) Well, I reckon you got
some pretty lousy scouts, then.

35
00:02:46,867 --> 00:02:49,641
Mexicans close by. There's hundreds of 'em.

36
00:02:49,671 --> 00:02:52,722
Colonel, you want that I
should go ride for help?

37
00:02:52,840 --> 00:02:54,423
We're moving out. Pack it up.

38
00:02:54,508 --> 00:02:56,225
(Burns) We ought to
make a stand right here.

39
00:02:56,289 --> 00:02:57,588
Yeah, the boy's right.

40
00:02:57,613 --> 00:02:59,563
I don't want another Alamo on my hands.

41
00:02:59,678 --> 00:03:01,561
Yeah, we go out there,
it's gonna be a slaughter.

42
00:03:01,607 --> 00:03:03,390
Not if we make it out in time.

43
00:03:03,421 --> 00:03:05,414
(Fannin) Let's go! Let's
go! Prepare to march!

44
00:03:05,486 --> 00:03:06,518
- Pack all the essentials!
- You ain't listening, Colonel.

45
00:03:06,619 --> 00:03:08,369
They're here! Listen to us.

46
00:03:08,439 --> 00:03:10,105
- They're here. We seen 'em.
- Get on your horse!

47
00:03:10,191 --> 00:03:12,608
(Fannin) Let's go, boys! Move! Let's go.

48
00:03:12,693 --> 00:03:15,194
Take all the essentials.
Come on, let's go. Let's go.

49
00:03:15,279 --> 00:03:17,696
Let's go! Let's go!

50
00:03:17,765 --> 00:03:18,844
[dramatic music]

51
00:03:18,869 --> 00:03:19,914
♪ ♪

52
00:03:19,914 --> 00:03:24,648
_

53
00:03:42,440 --> 00:03:46,275
Your Excellency, pardon the intrusion.

54
00:03:46,394 --> 00:03:50,696
Our sentries captured a
prisoner riding from the north,

55
00:03:50,781 --> 00:03:53,365
but the rebel army is in Kent.

56
00:03:53,451 --> 00:03:56,402
Clearly, she belongs to
someone of importance.

57
00:03:56,487 --> 00:04:00,205
- No sign of a whip.
- I ain't common or a slave.

58
00:04:06,130 --> 00:04:09,415
Long ago I was contracted
as an indentured servant,

59
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:10,716
but I was freed.

60
00:04:14,839 --> 00:04:16,672
Remove your hands from her.

61
00:04:23,431 --> 00:04:26,870
What is your name, Señorita?

62
00:04:28,702 --> 00:04:32,421
Emily West... native New Orleans.

63
00:04:34,091 --> 00:04:40,379
You may go with Colonel
Almonte to answer his questions,

64
00:04:40,481 --> 00:04:44,433
or you may remain here and answer mine.

65
00:04:46,687 --> 00:04:49,571
Well, I believe I'd like to get to know

66
00:04:49,690 --> 00:04:52,557
His Excellency better.

67
00:04:52,660 --> 00:04:54,360
And so you will.

68
00:05:03,337 --> 00:05:05,454
I'll send for you.

69
00:05:31,399 --> 00:05:33,198
Of all the settlers in the Union,

70
00:05:33,284 --> 00:05:35,367
there ain't nobody left to fight for.

71
00:05:35,453 --> 00:05:37,569
God damned Fannin.

72
00:05:37,655 --> 00:05:40,072
He's a crow's egg in an eagle's nest.

73
00:05:42,293 --> 00:05:43,608
(man) Watch out!

74
00:05:43,711 --> 00:05:45,210
[crash]

75
00:05:47,214 --> 00:05:48,580
(Houston) What's the hold up there?

76
00:05:51,252 --> 00:05:53,168
(man) Yah, yah! Come on.

77
00:05:53,254 --> 00:05:54,803
Push!

78
00:05:57,475 --> 00:05:58,557
God damned wagon.

79
00:05:58,642 --> 00:06:00,292
(woman) Keep pushing!

80
00:06:00,401 --> 00:06:03,302
God damned Fannin. God damned every...

81
00:06:03,397 --> 00:06:05,314
God damned patriot.

82
00:06:05,433 --> 00:06:08,767
He thinks he can win this war on his own.

83
00:06:11,772 --> 00:06:14,356
[coughing]

84
00:06:21,665 --> 00:06:25,367
(Houston) Deaf, what's the
doc say about your condition?

85
00:06:27,505 --> 00:06:30,956
Ain't nothing changed since
he gave me the long face.

86
00:06:31,041 --> 00:06:33,092
Don't you never mind.

87
00:06:42,103 --> 00:06:43,302
(man) Sam?

88
00:06:45,306 --> 00:06:47,306
Hope Miss Emily's feeling better.

89
00:06:50,611 --> 00:06:53,145
Sorry to hear she gone off.

90
00:06:57,451 --> 00:06:59,684
That Tejano Ranger, Flores...

91
00:06:59,787 --> 00:07:02,521
He's sweeping for stragglers with Anderson.

92
00:07:02,623 --> 00:07:05,023
Summon him up for me.

93
00:07:21,675 --> 00:07:26,061
My suspicion is that you
are running away from a man.

94
00:07:27,815 --> 00:07:31,150
Now, why do you suspect that?

95
00:07:31,235 --> 00:07:34,069
I just do.

96
00:07:34,188 --> 00:07:37,606
Well, I like to think I
might be running to something.

97
00:07:37,691 --> 00:07:39,575
(Almonte) General...

98
00:07:44,081 --> 00:07:46,114
I'm in the middle of lunch.

99
00:07:46,200 --> 00:07:47,332
I'm sorry.

100
00:07:47,418 --> 00:07:49,451
It's important, Your Excellency.

101
00:07:54,458 --> 00:07:57,709
[whispering]

102
00:08:02,265 --> 00:08:04,182
Your vigilance is commendable,

103
00:08:04,207 --> 00:08:06,674
but I will handle the interrogation.

104
00:08:09,056 --> 00:08:10,722
Yes, Your Excellency.

105
00:08:19,483 --> 00:08:21,700
My man discovered an interesting monogram

106
00:08:21,785 --> 00:08:24,936
on your saddle.

107
00:08:25,039 --> 00:08:26,974
"S.H."

108
00:08:29,543 --> 00:08:31,293
S.H.:

109
00:08:31,412 --> 00:08:35,110
could that stand for Samuel Houston?

110
00:08:36,050 --> 00:08:38,617
Hmm?

111
00:08:38,719 --> 00:08:42,954
This is the man you are running from?

112
00:08:43,057 --> 00:08:46,391
He wasn't the man I thought he was.

113
00:08:46,477 --> 00:08:50,012
And why is that?

114
00:08:50,097 --> 00:08:53,632
I saw the look of defeat on his face

115
00:08:53,734 --> 00:08:55,317
when he heard what happened at the Alamo.

116
00:08:59,573 --> 00:09:02,574
Well, now you are here.

117
00:09:02,660 --> 00:09:04,539
What do you want?

118
00:09:11,285 --> 00:09:16,088
I want a warm bath

119
00:09:16,173 --> 00:09:18,340
with you in it.

120
00:09:21,687 --> 00:09:23,516
[dramatic music]

121
00:09:23,541 --> 00:09:24,734
♪ ♪

122
00:09:24,734 --> 00:09:29,199
_

123
00:09:41,315 --> 00:09:45,233
[men clicking tongues and whistling]

124
00:09:45,319 --> 00:09:54,209
♪ ♪

125
00:09:54,936 --> 00:09:58,637
We get past this ridge,
men, and we're safe!

126
00:09:58,662 --> 00:10:00,695
On the double! Let's go!

127
00:10:01,168 --> 00:10:07,339
♪ ♪

128
00:10:07,424 --> 00:10:10,425
[men shouting]

129
00:10:15,349 --> 00:10:17,215
Fall back! Fall back!

130
00:10:17,318 --> 00:10:18,483
Move! Move! Move!

131
00:10:18,569 --> 00:10:20,185
[bugle calling]

132
00:10:25,409 --> 00:10:33,415
♪ ♪

133
00:10:42,209 --> 00:10:43,342
Ah!

134
00:10:43,427 --> 00:10:51,433
♪ ♪

135
00:10:55,272 --> 00:10:57,105
(Fannin) Defend your positions!
Defend your positions!

136
00:10:57,224 --> 00:10:58,440
Fire!

137
00:11:00,227 --> 00:11:03,311
[screaming]

138
00:11:03,397 --> 00:11:06,648
Colonel's shot! Yance, give me a hand!

139
00:11:06,734 --> 00:11:08,150
Hang on, Colonel!

140
00:11:10,738 --> 00:11:12,204
We got you! Hang on!

141
00:11:12,289 --> 00:11:14,406
My leg! My leg!

142
00:11:18,712 --> 00:11:21,079
Wallace, send scouts to Houston!

143
00:11:21,165 --> 00:11:23,465
(Wallace) [shouts]

144
00:11:23,584 --> 00:11:25,584
Houston ain't sending no
one! He's done warned you!

145
00:11:25,669 --> 00:11:27,419
(Fannin) You must go!

146
00:11:29,640 --> 00:11:32,123
Defend your positions! Spread out!

147
00:11:32,226 --> 00:11:33,667
Spread 'em!

148
00:11:35,712 --> 00:11:37,212
Boy, come here! My leg!

149
00:11:37,312 --> 00:11:45,318
♪ ♪

150
00:11:52,946 --> 00:11:54,562
General Urrea...

151
00:11:54,648 --> 00:11:56,781
Tell Santa Anna we have
surrounded the rebels.

152
00:11:56,867 --> 00:11:59,234
His Excellency will not accept surrender.

153
00:11:59,319 --> 00:12:00,702
You must finish them.

154
00:12:00,821 --> 00:12:03,571
I am not a butcher.

155
00:12:03,657 --> 00:12:05,707
I will deliver your message.

156
00:12:11,548 --> 00:12:13,632
(Burns) Come on! This
way, Truett! Over here!

157
00:12:16,553 --> 00:12:18,503
How the hell did Fannin become Colonel?

158
00:12:18,588 --> 00:12:20,472
Must have married well.

159
00:12:22,676 --> 00:12:26,177
[bugle calling]

160
00:12:26,263 --> 00:12:27,562
What's that sound?

161
00:12:27,681 --> 00:12:28,813
The hell's that?

162
00:12:28,899 --> 00:12:31,816
[drum and bugle corps playing]

163
00:12:31,902 --> 00:12:34,385
♪ ♪

164
00:12:34,488 --> 00:12:36,321
They're messing with us.

165
00:12:41,578 --> 00:12:45,280
[pleasant folk music playing]

166
00:12:45,365 --> 00:12:50,752
♪ ♪

167
00:12:50,871 --> 00:12:55,457
[all singing in Spanish]

168
00:12:55,542 --> 00:13:03,515
♪ ♪

169
00:13:19,282 --> 00:13:27,288
♪ ♪

170
00:13:47,594 --> 00:13:51,763
[cheers and applause]

171
00:13:51,848 --> 00:13:54,966
Tonight, my countrymen,

172
00:13:55,068 --> 00:13:59,237
we not only celebrate
our successes in battle,

173
00:13:59,422 --> 00:14:01,840
but the total victory to come.

174
00:14:01,925 --> 00:14:04,408
You stand in San Durant.

175
00:14:04,511 --> 00:14:08,513
[cheers and applause]

176
00:14:08,598 --> 00:14:11,299
Chupaldo, where are you? I don't see you.

177
00:14:11,384 --> 00:14:14,519
[all exclaiming]

178
00:14:17,858 --> 00:14:20,758
I'll give you the great
honor to dispatch this message

179
00:14:20,861 --> 00:14:23,900
on the flag of truce to General Houston.

180
00:14:26,433 --> 00:14:29,601
This message says,

181
00:14:29,703 --> 00:14:31,870
"There will be no refuge, no escape,

182
00:14:31,955 --> 00:14:36,407
"no surrender, no mercy.

183
00:14:36,493 --> 00:14:40,328
"You will be hunted down, butchered,

184
00:14:40,413 --> 00:14:43,464
"and fed to my pigs!

185
00:14:43,583 --> 00:14:49,003
And then, in turn, we will
feast on you in celebration."

186
00:14:49,089 --> 00:14:52,627
[cheers and applause]

187
00:14:54,928 --> 00:14:56,071
Compañeros!

188
00:14:56,096 --> 00:14:59,347
(woman) Vamonos!

189
00:14:59,432 --> 00:15:02,517
Tomorrow, they might take our lives,

190
00:15:02,602 --> 00:15:05,436
but never our spirit...

191
00:15:05,522 --> 00:15:07,822
the Mexican spirit!

192
00:15:07,941 --> 00:15:09,357
[cheers and applause]

193
00:15:09,442 --> 00:15:11,976
<i>Musica!</i>

194
00:15:12,078 --> 00:15:15,530
♪ ♪

195
00:15:15,615 --> 00:15:18,616
[fireworks whizzing and crackling]

196
00:15:22,339 --> 00:15:25,456
The men need that kind of thing.

197
00:15:25,542 --> 00:15:30,762
(man) Señor Presidente,
General Urrea has Fannin trapped.

198
00:15:30,847 --> 00:15:34,632
By morning, he will have the
surrender of over 300 prisoners.

199
00:15:34,718 --> 00:15:36,384
Prisoners?

200
00:15:36,469 --> 00:15:40,521
Those men are fighting
under no recognized flag.

201
00:15:40,640 --> 00:15:44,309
The rules of war do not apply.

202
00:15:44,394 --> 00:15:46,778
Don Antonio,

203
00:15:46,863 --> 00:15:49,614
it's the Easter celebration.

204
00:15:49,699 --> 00:15:52,483
Perhaps mercy would be
the Christian thing to do.

205
00:15:52,569 --> 00:15:55,353
Christian?

206
00:15:55,455 --> 00:16:00,992
They are from the devil, not Jesus,

207
00:16:01,077 --> 00:16:04,935
and there will be no resurrection.

208
00:16:09,386 --> 00:16:12,387
[bugle calling]

209
00:16:15,425 --> 00:16:18,426
[crickets chirping]

210
00:16:24,230 --> 00:16:26,114
(Burns) Fannin should've
listened to Houston.

211
00:16:26,202 --> 00:16:29,654
(Fincham) You think we'll
get out of here alive?

212
00:16:29,739 --> 00:16:31,822
I wonder what Sarah's doing right now.

213
00:16:31,908 --> 00:16:33,624
Don't you be thinking about my gal.

214
00:16:33,710 --> 00:16:35,543
No.

215
00:16:35,662 --> 00:16:37,861
(Samuel Wallace) Get some sleep, boys.

216
00:16:37,964 --> 00:16:40,998
Urrea won't try another
attack till morning.

217
00:16:41,084 --> 00:16:43,718
[sighs]

218
00:16:43,836 --> 00:16:45,624
Got no need to hurry.

219
00:16:48,925 --> 00:16:51,709
Feel like I've been ate by a wolf.

220
00:16:51,811 --> 00:16:56,013
Yeah, and shit off a cliff.

221
00:16:58,851 --> 00:17:01,652
You boys brothers?

222
00:17:01,738 --> 00:17:05,690
Nah, he's too ugly to be relation.

223
00:17:05,775 --> 00:17:07,742
Yeah, well, he's too stupid.

224
00:17:10,363 --> 00:17:12,747
I got a brother.

225
00:17:12,865 --> 00:17:14,915
We call him Bigfoot

226
00:17:15,034 --> 00:17:18,085
on account of he once killed
an Injun with big feet.

227
00:17:21,290 --> 00:17:22,873
Our pap...

228
00:17:22,959 --> 00:17:25,760
he's a Virginia blacksmith.

229
00:17:25,878 --> 00:17:30,715
He made us these matching
wrist cuffs to bond us.

230
00:17:41,484 --> 00:17:44,068
I hope like hell to see him again.

231
00:17:45,039 --> 00:17:48,240
[soft music]

232
00:17:48,350 --> 00:17:53,887
♪ ♪

233
00:17:53,958 --> 00:17:57,409
- General?
- Come in.

234
00:17:57,711 --> 00:18:00,495
If those Ranger boys don't
come back with Fannin,

235
00:18:00,581 --> 00:18:02,381
I'm cutting him loose.

236
00:18:02,466 --> 00:18:04,966
Captains... misters Truett and Yancey,

237
00:18:05,085 --> 00:18:08,053
are due to report back tomorrow.

238
00:18:08,138 --> 00:18:09,421
Have a seat.

239
00:18:09,506 --> 00:18:11,256
Sir.

240
00:18:11,341 --> 00:18:14,559
Would you like a cigar?

241
00:18:14,645 --> 00:18:16,311
Sir, thank you.

242
00:18:22,887 --> 00:18:23,886
[spits]

243
00:18:33,047 --> 00:18:36,782
Señor Flores,

244
00:18:36,884 --> 00:18:40,786
I need a volunteer to
infiltrate Santa Anna's camp;

245
00:18:40,888 --> 00:18:44,189
assess the size and
readiness of his troops.

246
00:18:44,291 --> 00:18:47,326
What say you?

247
00:18:47,428 --> 00:18:49,995
I'd be awake, beast to hand, if I could.

248
00:18:50,097 --> 00:18:51,363
Very good.

249
00:18:54,051 --> 00:18:55,700
Yes, sir.

250
00:18:55,803 --> 00:18:58,003
I want you to find out
if Emily West is there.

251
00:18:58,088 --> 00:19:01,890
If she's in trouble, I
need you to get her out.

252
00:19:02,009 --> 00:19:03,675
She can be high-strung,

253
00:19:03,761 --> 00:19:07,846
but you strike me as a man who
can handle a spirited woman.

254
00:19:09,850 --> 00:19:14,153
(Santa Anna) Very clever of
Houston to send you to spy on me.

255
00:19:14,238 --> 00:19:17,856
(West) He tried to stop me.

256
00:19:17,942 --> 00:19:19,891
I came on my own.

257
00:19:19,994 --> 00:19:22,327
He tried to stop you?

258
00:19:22,413 --> 00:19:25,948
I thought he barely noticed you were gone.

259
00:19:26,033 --> 00:19:30,402
Well, we had a fiery affair.

260
00:19:30,504 --> 00:19:35,791
It was a blaze so scorching,
it consumed itself,

261
00:19:35,876 --> 00:19:39,077
then he grew cold to the touch.

262
00:19:39,180 --> 00:19:41,263
I am cold.

263
00:19:45,219 --> 00:19:49,638
Well, then, I must make certain

264
00:19:49,723 --> 00:19:55,394
that you stay very, very warm.

265
00:20:02,369 --> 00:20:03,869
Opium.

266
00:20:03,954 --> 00:20:06,428
Romulo, bring the pipe.

267
00:20:14,965 --> 00:20:19,718
"I have no fear of an army of lions

268
00:20:19,803 --> 00:20:22,804
"led by your sheep,

269
00:20:22,923 --> 00:20:30,679
but I do have fear of an army
of sheep led by your lion."

270
00:20:30,764 --> 00:20:34,266
Alexander the Great.

271
00:20:34,351 --> 00:20:40,155
Which one is he... a sheep or lion?

272
00:20:40,274 --> 00:20:44,152
Well, is it me you want

273
00:20:44,177 --> 00:20:47,178
or General Houston?

274
00:20:48,865 --> 00:20:50,532
I have you.

275
00:20:54,955 --> 00:20:55,870
Ah!

276
00:20:55,956 --> 00:21:00,458
But do not think I am fooled.

277
00:21:00,544 --> 00:21:04,262
I know that a sweet-scented yellow rose

278
00:21:04,347 --> 00:21:09,634
like you has sharp thorns.

279
00:21:13,390 --> 00:21:19,310
Perhaps on occasion,

280
00:21:19,396 --> 00:21:22,947
but tonight...

281
00:21:23,033 --> 00:21:27,235
I'm the one who's gonna be pricked.

282
00:21:27,320 --> 00:21:28,820
[moans]

283
00:21:31,840 --> 00:21:34,496
[drum and bugle corps playing]

284
00:21:34,522 --> 00:21:40,025
♪ ♪

285
00:21:40,083 --> 00:21:41,533
(man) Over there!

286
00:21:41,618 --> 00:21:43,952
(man) I see 'em! We'll lead the line!

287
00:21:44,037 --> 00:21:45,620
(Samuel Wallace) Wake up, boys. Wake up.

288
00:21:45,706 --> 00:21:47,172
Wake up. Wake up.

289
00:21:47,257 --> 00:21:49,040
We can hear 'em clicking and signaling.

290
00:21:49,126 --> 00:21:51,459
It's time to get ready to
fight. Wake up. Wake up, boys.

291
00:21:51,545 --> 00:21:54,346
- I hate this damned music.
- That's what they want.

292
00:21:55,516 --> 00:21:56,643
[whistles]

293
00:22:04,641 --> 00:22:05,991
[bullets whizzing]

294
00:22:16,069 --> 00:22:18,904
[moaning]

295
00:22:18,989 --> 00:22:23,208
Yance! Yance, I... I can't see!

296
00:22:23,293 --> 00:22:25,627
- Help!
- I can't see!

297
00:22:25,746 --> 00:22:27,445
- Somebody, we need bandages!
- I can't see!

298
00:22:27,548 --> 00:22:29,464
Help! Come on, buddy. Come on.

299
00:22:29,583 --> 00:22:31,082
Am I gonna die?

300
00:22:31,168 --> 00:22:33,468
No, no, no, no, you're not gonna die.

301
00:22:33,587 --> 00:22:35,170
Come on. Come on, buddy.

302
00:22:35,255 --> 00:22:36,621
- Am I gonna die?
- Come on, buddy.

303
00:22:36,723 --> 00:22:38,289
- Am I gonna die?
- You're not gonna die!

304
00:22:38,392 --> 00:22:40,141
No. You ain't!

305
00:22:40,260 --> 00:22:43,261
[both shouting]

306
00:22:44,598 --> 00:22:45,630
Come on!

307
00:22:45,732 --> 00:22:48,266
Help me! Help!

308
00:22:53,273 --> 00:22:55,273
Come on, partner.

309
00:22:57,361 --> 00:22:59,411
We supposed to be heroes.

310
00:22:59,496 --> 00:23:01,145
(Samuel Wallace) Come on, son.

311
00:23:01,248 --> 00:23:02,480
- It ain't over yet.
- You're all right.

312
00:23:02,583 --> 00:23:04,115
You've got yourself to look out for.

313
00:23:04,201 --> 00:23:06,001
- Come on.
- I'll make it count.

314
00:23:06,119 --> 00:23:08,286
Deaf and the Rangers
will get us out of this.

315
00:23:08,372 --> 00:23:10,922
No, you stay with me. You'll die out there.

316
00:23:11,008 --> 00:23:14,342
Rangers don't take no
orders from the damn army!

317
00:23:14,461 --> 00:23:17,545
[boom]

318
00:23:17,631 --> 00:23:20,215
I'm going for help! I'm... I'm going for...

319
00:23:23,387 --> 00:23:26,304
It's all right. It's all
right. It's all right.

320
00:23:26,390 --> 00:23:27,522
We're going, girl.

321
00:23:27,641 --> 00:23:29,140
We're going. Come on, girl.

322
00:23:29,226 --> 00:23:31,509
All right...

323
00:23:31,612 --> 00:23:33,445
We're going to get Houston!

324
00:23:33,530 --> 00:23:36,014
We're going to get General Houston!

325
00:23:36,116 --> 00:23:42,520
♪ ♪

326
00:23:42,623 --> 00:23:46,291
Pull the cannon. Advance the cannons!

327
00:23:49,746 --> 00:23:57,752
♪ ♪

328
00:24:01,008 --> 00:24:03,174
[men shouting]

329
00:24:14,488 --> 00:24:22,494
♪ ♪

330
00:24:25,999 --> 00:24:27,398
[grunts]

331
00:24:27,501 --> 00:24:29,117
(man) Nice shootin'.

332
00:24:31,103 --> 00:24:37,700
♪ ♪

333
00:24:39,018 --> 00:24:39,868
[jubilant music]

334
00:24:39,893 --> 00:24:42,914
_

335
00:24:42,939 --> 00:24:44,672
(man) Break camp.

336
00:24:44,697 --> 00:24:45,960
Today's detail.

337
00:24:45,985 --> 00:24:50,654
We sweep these valleys for
any wayward homesteaders.

338
00:24:50,739 --> 00:24:54,208
That means you, Gator.

339
00:24:54,526 --> 00:24:56,276
What do we do with him?

340
00:24:56,362 --> 00:24:59,029
Nothing. He's being executed.

341
00:24:59,114 --> 00:25:00,781
I reckon he can wait here shackled

342
00:25:00,866 --> 00:25:03,250
till the firing squad come.

343
00:25:03,369 --> 00:25:05,068
We ain't gonna wait.

344
00:25:05,170 --> 00:25:07,037
He already run off when he
weren't gonna be executed.

345
00:25:07,122 --> 00:25:08,455
No, no, no, no, gentlemen,
gentlemen, please.

346
00:25:08,540 --> 00:25:10,140
I will wait for 'em. I will.

347
00:25:10,209 --> 00:25:13,176
I will wait like you never
seen no one wait before.

348
00:25:13,262 --> 00:25:15,912
Please, just carry on
with your duties and chores

349
00:25:16,014 --> 00:25:18,131
and you can trust I ain't gonna do nothing

350
00:25:18,217 --> 00:25:22,219
but stay right here, on my honor.

351
00:25:22,304 --> 00:25:24,087
Let's shoot him.

352
00:25:24,489 --> 00:25:28,158
Whoa, it's a damned shame
to kill a man for pilfering.

353
00:25:28,243 --> 00:25:29,826
Man's got to eat, right?

354
00:25:29,911 --> 00:25:31,444
Are we supposed to execute him?

355
00:25:31,530 --> 00:25:32,579
Not a Ranger's job.

356
00:25:32,698 --> 00:25:34,531
The army convicted him.

357
00:25:34,616 --> 00:25:35,898
They shoot him.

358
00:25:36,001 --> 00:25:37,667
May I just suggest...

359
00:25:37,753 --> 00:25:40,336
I suggest you shut your hole.

360
00:25:40,422 --> 00:25:43,906
(Knowles) I'm only saying
why not just take me with you?

361
00:25:44,009 --> 00:25:45,842
Take me; make me do what-some-ever

362
00:25:45,927 --> 00:25:48,294
you might need me to do.

363
00:25:48,380 --> 00:25:51,297
I could... well... I
could carry your saddlebag.

364
00:25:51,383 --> 00:25:52,816
- I could...
- That's enough.

365
00:25:52,918 --> 00:25:53,917
[gunshot]

366
00:25:56,972 --> 00:25:59,422
(Anderson) Rangers are not
executioners, you reprobate.

367
00:26:03,561 --> 00:26:06,813
This man is right, if I may say so.

368
00:26:06,932 --> 00:26:08,798
Making sure people's safe from Mexicans...

369
00:26:08,900 --> 00:26:10,400
that's a whole hell of a lot more important

370
00:26:10,485 --> 00:26:12,769
than shooting some no-account deserter

371
00:26:12,854 --> 00:26:13,970
like myself.

372
00:26:14,072 --> 00:26:15,738
I ain't worth it.

373
00:26:15,824 --> 00:26:17,490
I ain't nowhere near worth it.

374
00:26:17,609 --> 00:26:19,359
That's for damned sure.

375
00:26:19,444 --> 00:26:22,495
Hell, you ain't even
worth the shot and powder.

376
00:26:22,614 --> 00:26:24,814
You know what? You're
clearly a very smart man.

377
00:26:24,916 --> 00:26:26,983
That's right. I am.

378
00:26:27,085 --> 00:26:28,785
Still say we shoot him.

379
00:26:31,790 --> 00:26:33,172
Well, well...

380
00:26:35,126 --> 00:26:37,326
You agree not to rabbit off...

381
00:26:37,429 --> 00:26:39,662
lend us a hand while we help
get these settlers to safety?

382
00:26:39,764 --> 00:26:42,882
Course... innocent settler...
that was what I was doing before.

383
00:26:42,968 --> 00:26:45,885
(Anderson) You do not
charge for your services.

384
00:26:45,971 --> 00:26:47,309
- Right.
- No tricks.

385
00:26:47,334 --> 00:26:48,450
No.

386
00:26:48,475 --> 00:26:49,832
Or I will let Vern shoot you.

387
00:26:49,858 --> 00:26:51,774
Yes, sir. I swear.

388
00:26:51,860 --> 00:26:53,509
I swear.

389
00:26:53,611 --> 00:26:54,694
But if I may just one...

390
00:26:54,813 --> 00:26:56,529
make one last suggestion,

391
00:26:56,648 --> 00:27:01,367
I still don't quite understand
how we can do something

392
00:27:01,486 --> 00:27:05,621
and then not getting
anywhere near paid for it.

393
00:27:05,707 --> 00:27:06,706
Just saying.

394
00:27:08,827 --> 00:27:16,833
♪ ♪

395
00:27:37,022 --> 00:27:39,822
You dug up the chest?

396
00:27:39,908 --> 00:27:41,774
You and the little one are gonna need money

397
00:27:41,860 --> 00:27:44,360
when you go to Victoria.

398
00:27:44,446 --> 00:27:46,446
I'm not going anywhere without you.

399
00:27:46,531 --> 00:27:47,830
Yes, you is.

400
00:27:47,916 --> 00:27:49,899
Them Mexicans bastards are coming.

401
00:27:50,001 --> 00:27:52,418
Deaf, I'm Mexican.

402
00:27:52,537 --> 00:27:53,920
And so was I.

403
00:27:54,039 --> 00:27:55,705
And now we's Texian.

404
00:27:58,543 --> 00:27:59,625
Damn it.

405
00:28:04,849 --> 00:28:07,050
[goats bleating]

406
00:28:17,763 --> 00:28:21,264
Lupe...

407
00:28:21,349 --> 00:28:22,482
[sighs]

408
00:28:22,601 --> 00:28:24,744
You're right. I'm sorry.

409
00:28:24,769 --> 00:28:26,803
That was very...

410
00:28:26,888 --> 00:28:29,305
it was a poor choice of words.

411
00:28:29,391 --> 00:28:32,275
But you ain't seen what I seen.

412
00:28:32,360 --> 00:28:34,610
This ain't about us.

413
00:28:34,796 --> 00:28:36,445
It's about a tyrant we can't abide by.

414
00:28:36,548 --> 00:28:37,914
You know that.

415
00:28:41,169 --> 00:28:42,835
Lupe.

416
00:28:48,726 --> 00:28:51,644
I ain't seen Half Breed.

417
00:28:51,763 --> 00:28:55,481
He comes and goes; got a mind of his own.

418
00:28:55,600 --> 00:28:57,266
He's a smart dog...

419
00:28:57,352 --> 00:28:59,602
knows when to get,

420
00:28:59,687 --> 00:29:02,271
which is what you got to
do till we whoop Santa Anna.

421
00:29:02,357 --> 00:29:04,407
And if you don't?

422
00:29:04,492 --> 00:29:07,276
Well, then, it ain't gonna matter, Lupe.

423
00:29:07,362 --> 00:29:08,678
We'll all be dead.

424
00:29:15,120 --> 00:29:19,321
(Anderson) Shrewsbury, we are the Rangers!

425
00:29:19,424 --> 00:29:20,590
We're here to help!

426
00:29:20,675 --> 00:29:21,841
By order of the Texian government,

427
00:29:21,960 --> 00:29:24,760
you must evacuate to safety.

428
00:29:24,846 --> 00:29:26,458
Shrewsbury!

429
00:29:30,885 --> 00:29:33,719
We gonna take a gander inside?

430
00:29:33,805 --> 00:29:36,165
Let's send this hear wormy feller in.

431
00:29:36,190 --> 00:29:38,691
It's high time he learned a
thing or two about rangering.

432
00:29:38,776 --> 00:29:40,776
[laughter]

433
00:29:40,862 --> 00:29:42,328
(Knowles) Wormy...
that's good. That's good.

434
00:29:42,447 --> 00:29:44,947
I see what you're doing,
but the thing is, gentlemen.

435
00:29:45,032 --> 00:29:46,866
I just ain't dumb,

436
00:29:46,951 --> 00:29:48,751
so it ain't hard for me to see
there is no reason whatsoever

437
00:29:48,836 --> 00:29:50,369
for me to go in there.

438
00:29:50,455 --> 00:29:51,653
Ain't scared, is you?

439
00:29:51,678 --> 00:29:52,760
Ho!

440
00:29:52,924 --> 00:29:54,557
- You saying I's yellow?
- Yep.

441
00:29:54,642 --> 00:29:56,788
- Youse born yellow.
- You saying I's...

442
00:29:56,813 --> 00:29:58,312
Yellow as your damned shirt.

443
00:29:58,337 --> 00:30:00,387
- Get on in there.
- Is that a fact?

444
00:30:02,767 --> 00:30:06,652
All right, well...

445
00:30:06,771 --> 00:30:09,155
I... y'all at least gonna give
me a damned pistol or something?

446
00:30:09,274 --> 00:30:11,023
(Anderson) We got you covered.

447
00:30:11,109 --> 00:30:12,525
(Knowles) All right.

448
00:30:17,865 --> 00:30:18,998
Ah!

449
00:30:22,954 --> 00:30:25,838
[ominous music]

450
00:30:25,957 --> 00:30:33,963
♪ ♪

451
00:30:37,302 --> 00:30:39,101
[door creaks]

452
00:30:44,942 --> 00:30:52,948
♪ ♪

453
00:30:53,034 --> 00:30:54,400
"Gone for licker."

454
00:30:54,485 --> 00:30:56,869
[clattering]

455
00:30:56,988 --> 00:30:58,904
Who's that in there?

456
00:30:58,990 --> 00:31:00,156
Who's that in there?

457
00:31:03,711 --> 00:31:05,044
You best answer me!

458
00:31:10,501 --> 00:31:12,468
The Rangers come to help!

459
00:31:12,553 --> 00:31:16,088
♪ ♪

460
00:31:16,174 --> 00:31:17,890
[pig squealing]

461
00:31:19,894 --> 00:31:21,677
[gunshots]

462
00:31:21,763 --> 00:31:23,686
Whoo-hoo! Whoo!

463
00:31:23,711 --> 00:31:27,910
Damned pig 'bout broke my damned leg.

464
00:31:27,935 --> 00:31:29,615
Whoa.

465
00:31:29,709 --> 00:31:31,153
(Anderson) Is there anyone home?

466
00:31:31,239 --> 00:31:33,022
You done good, Knowles.

467
00:31:33,107 --> 00:31:35,074
Then again, it is starting to look a lot

468
00:31:35,193 --> 00:31:37,910
like bacon and ham hocks for supper.

469
00:31:38,029 --> 00:31:40,896
[laughs]

470
00:31:40,998 --> 00:31:42,081
(man) Whoa.

471
00:31:42,200 --> 00:31:43,899
- We got pork for supper.
- Whoo!

472
00:31:44,001 --> 00:31:46,085
(Knowles) We gonna be
eating fine tonight. Hoo-hoo!

473
00:31:46,204 --> 00:31:47,903
Truett and Yancey report in yet?

474
00:31:48,005 --> 00:31:49,538
They haven't. I hadn't seen hide or hair.

475
00:31:49,624 --> 00:31:51,841
We best report back to Houston.

476
00:31:51,926 --> 00:31:52,875
Let's go.

477
00:31:52,960 --> 00:32:04,587
♪ ♪

478
00:32:05,723 --> 00:32:08,641
[ominous music]

479
00:32:08,726 --> 00:32:16,732
♪ ♪

480
00:32:37,922 --> 00:32:39,814
Don't be too hard on 'em, Colonel.

481
00:32:39,839 --> 00:32:41,973
They got their pride too.

482
00:32:43,928 --> 00:32:45,461
I cannot offer you terms.

483
00:32:45,563 --> 00:32:48,731
You must surrender at discretion.

484
00:32:48,816 --> 00:32:49,899
If you won't grant their lives,

485
00:32:49,984 --> 00:32:51,100
my men will keep killing Mexicans

486
00:32:51,185 --> 00:32:52,852
until their last breath.

487
00:32:52,937 --> 00:32:55,020
Surrender, Colonel.

488
00:32:55,106 --> 00:32:57,773
I will see that your men are
fed and taken back to Goliad

489
00:32:57,859 --> 00:32:59,975
as prisoners.

490
00:33:00,077 --> 00:33:01,827
If you give me your assurance
that my men will be treated

491
00:33:01,946 --> 00:33:05,164
under the rules of war.

492
00:33:05,283 --> 00:33:09,752
I will appeal on your
behalf to General Santa Anna.

493
00:33:09,837 --> 00:33:12,379
I suppose that's the best I can do.

494
00:33:29,307 --> 00:33:32,454
I rely on your honest effort!

495
00:33:40,351 --> 00:33:41,613
(Flores) Come on, Señor Beans.

496
00:33:41,638 --> 00:33:44,386
[speaking Spanish]

497
00:33:44,488 --> 00:33:46,388
(Gator) I think it's about time
to cut that up there, Beans.

498
00:33:46,490 --> 00:33:48,190
We all might hungry over here.

499
00:33:48,275 --> 00:33:50,993
Hey, I'm so starved I
could eat the south end

500
00:33:51,078 --> 00:33:52,611
of a northbound goat, but it ain't ready.

501
00:33:52,696 --> 00:33:54,496
Get your damned hand out of there.

502
00:33:54,582 --> 00:33:56,331
Why don't you just hush
up? All of y'all hush up.

503
00:33:56,417 --> 00:33:58,233
The only one that's gonna
be carving that porker

504
00:33:58,335 --> 00:34:01,703
right there will be none other
than this gentleman right here.

505
00:34:01,789 --> 00:34:05,541
Why? 'Cause who's the
one who flushed him out?

506
00:34:05,626 --> 00:34:07,459
Who's the one who flushed him out?

507
00:34:07,545 --> 00:34:11,013
Now, what I remember is this
little piggy flushing you out.

508
00:34:11,098 --> 00:34:12,514
[laughter]

509
00:34:12,600 --> 00:34:13,715
(Knowles) I can see you gentlemen

510
00:34:13,801 --> 00:34:15,934
are doing your damnedest

511
00:34:16,053 --> 00:34:18,587
to overlook the fact that I
risked me my damned behind.

512
00:34:18,689 --> 00:34:21,023
That pretty little Señorita
that Truett and Yancey

513
00:34:21,108 --> 00:34:23,525
are sweet on...

514
00:34:23,611 --> 00:34:28,096
she must need comforting
with them boys gone.

515
00:34:28,198 --> 00:34:30,532
Watch yourself, Vern.

516
00:34:30,618 --> 00:34:33,346
You know that's Doc Ewing's daughter.

517
00:34:35,239 --> 00:34:38,156
He married a Mexican?

518
00:34:38,242 --> 00:34:40,993
Tejana.

519
00:34:41,078 --> 00:34:46,681
Doc won't ever talk about it,
but she's not around no more.

520
00:34:48,385 --> 00:34:51,670
Poor thing; no mama.

521
00:34:51,755 --> 00:34:54,456
Don't pester that girl, Vern,

522
00:34:54,558 --> 00:34:58,226
or her father will
shoot you where it hurts.

523
00:35:03,767 --> 00:35:11,773
♪ ♪

524
00:35:16,413 --> 00:35:18,330
<i>Buenos tardes.</i>

525
00:35:18,449 --> 00:35:20,332
[chuckles]

526
00:35:20,357 --> 00:35:22,607
That's all right. I got it.

527
00:35:22,786 --> 00:35:25,558
You ought never to have
to work a day in your life.

528
00:35:30,010 --> 00:35:32,511
Allow me.

529
00:35:32,630 --> 00:35:34,713
This is how they do in the islands,

530
00:35:34,798 --> 00:35:35,964
only they don't use no hands.

531
00:35:36,050 --> 00:35:37,382
All right, just give me my basket.

532
00:35:37,468 --> 00:35:38,717
And they dance the live long day.

533
00:35:38,802 --> 00:35:40,435
Please, give me my basket now!

534
00:35:40,521 --> 00:35:42,270
(Doc Ewing) Sarah!

535
00:35:42,356 --> 00:35:45,548
Get your basket, Sarah, and get on inside.

536
00:35:49,363 --> 00:35:51,563
Doc.

537
00:35:51,649 --> 00:35:53,649
[whistling]

538
00:35:58,822 --> 00:36:01,823
[indistinct chatter]

539
00:36:12,336 --> 00:36:19,641
♪ My faith looks up to thee ♪

540
00:36:19,727 --> 00:36:26,565
(all) ♪ Thou lamb of Calvary ♪

541
00:36:26,684 --> 00:36:32,187
♪ Savior divine ♪

542
00:36:32,272 --> 00:36:37,225
(man) General Portilla,
where are you taking my men?

543
00:36:37,327 --> 00:36:39,194
I should be with them!

544
00:36:39,279 --> 00:36:40,529
(Portilla) You couldn't keep up.

545
00:36:40,614 --> 00:36:43,331
You will have to be shot like a lame horse.

546
00:36:43,417 --> 00:36:45,534
General Urrea promised...

547
00:36:45,619 --> 00:36:47,169
promised!

548
00:36:47,254 --> 00:36:49,621
He does not speak for General Santa Anna.

549
00:36:49,707 --> 00:36:51,873
He does not tolerate traitors.

550
00:37:00,310 --> 00:37:03,862
If I am to be executed, I
will be shot in the chest

551
00:37:03,887 --> 00:37:06,388
and buried like a Christian
in a box with a marker.

552
00:37:09,643 --> 00:37:13,261
And I request that you
send this watch to my family

553
00:37:13,363 --> 00:37:14,780
in Marion, Georgia.

554
00:37:31,582 --> 00:37:35,300
If you were a soldier...

555
00:37:35,419 --> 00:37:38,286
but you are a stinking wetback.

556
00:37:38,388 --> 00:37:42,841
You swam across the Sabine River,

557
00:37:42,926 --> 00:37:45,594
and you are here illegally

558
00:37:45,679 --> 00:37:47,979
in my country.

559
00:37:53,604 --> 00:37:57,489
[indistinct chatter]

560
00:37:57,608 --> 00:37:59,775
(man) Keep walking.

561
00:38:01,612 --> 00:38:10,418
♪ ♪

562
00:38:10,504 --> 00:38:13,421
(man) General Urrea's
army is approaching Goliad.

563
00:38:13,507 --> 00:38:15,156
(Houston) We got to get 'em out.

564
00:38:15,259 --> 00:38:18,159
[drum and bugle corps playing]

565
00:38:18,262 --> 00:38:26,635
♪ ♪

566
00:38:26,720 --> 00:38:30,555
Any news from your boys at Goliad?

567
00:38:30,641 --> 00:38:33,024
General, what are your orders?

568
00:38:35,896 --> 00:38:40,515
We must do what's prudent;
not what emotion dictates.

569
00:38:40,617 --> 00:38:42,400
Our enemy wants to
catch us out in the open,

570
00:38:42,486 --> 00:38:45,353
where numbers count.

571
00:38:45,455 --> 00:38:49,524
I can't risk us getting pincered
between Santa Anna's armies.

572
00:38:49,626 --> 00:38:51,459
The order stands.

573
00:38:51,545 --> 00:38:54,212
We will continue to withdraw east...

574
00:38:54,331 --> 00:38:57,499
stretch out their supply
lines... pick our ground.

575
00:38:57,584 --> 00:39:00,335
Withdraw, sir? The men
are already talking mutiny.

576
00:39:00,420 --> 00:39:02,504
Let 'em talk while they retreat.

577
00:39:02,589 --> 00:39:04,139
Yeah, but what about the dissidents

578
00:39:04,224 --> 00:39:06,207
like Baker and Sherman?

579
00:39:06,310 --> 00:39:09,427
- What should I tell them?
- Tell 'em to follow orders!

580
00:39:09,513 --> 00:39:13,598
These boys have maybe...
maybe one battle in 'em.

581
00:39:14,215 --> 00:39:15,931
If it comes at the wrong time,

582
00:39:16,037 --> 00:39:18,270
we all die.

583
00:39:18,355 --> 00:39:20,572
You men are in charge while I'm gone.

584
00:39:20,691 --> 00:39:22,324
You're leaving, sir?

585
00:39:22,409 --> 00:39:24,860
- Where to?
- Goliad.

586
00:39:24,945 --> 00:39:27,162
I can't afford to lose those men.

587
00:39:27,247 --> 00:39:28,730
- But, General...
- Drill the volunteers.

588
00:39:28,832 --> 00:39:30,582
Discipline 'em. Make 'em an army.

589
00:39:30,701 --> 00:39:32,901
That is all. Rally the Rangers.

590
00:39:33,003 --> 00:39:34,669
I am personally pulling Fannin's head

591
00:39:34,755 --> 00:39:37,717
out of his puckered West Point ass.

592
00:39:40,377 --> 00:39:41,710
You heard the man.

593
00:39:41,795 --> 00:39:43,628
Let's make an army.

594
00:39:43,714 --> 00:39:46,715
[indistinct chatter]

595
00:39:50,387 --> 00:39:58,476
♪ ♪

596
00:39:58,562 --> 00:40:01,229
They said they were putting
us on a boat to Matamoros.

597
00:40:01,315 --> 00:40:02,814
This road's to Victoria.

598
00:40:02,900 --> 00:40:05,817
I don't think they're
taking us to either place.

599
00:40:10,584 --> 00:40:11,717
(man) Take water.

600
00:40:11,742 --> 00:40:14,242
♪ ♪

601
00:40:14,328 --> 00:40:16,277
(man) Water!

602
00:40:16,380 --> 00:40:19,381
[indistinct chatter]

603
00:40:28,425 --> 00:40:29,841
(man) Drink up. Drink up.

604
00:40:29,927 --> 00:40:31,927
All right.

605
00:40:32,012 --> 00:40:33,311
Orderly, men.

606
00:40:33,430 --> 00:40:34,346
Orderly.

607
00:40:34,431 --> 00:40:35,347
Single file line;

608
00:40:35,432 --> 00:40:36,898
we will all get our water.

609
00:40:36,984 --> 00:40:39,734
We're not animals.

610
00:40:39,820 --> 00:40:42,237
(Wallace) Come get your water.

611
00:40:42,322 --> 00:40:45,273
Water, men... single file line.

612
00:40:45,359 --> 00:40:49,444
[bugle playing]

613
00:40:53,834 --> 00:40:56,918
[indistinct chatter]

614
00:40:58,505 --> 00:41:00,321
What is going on?

615
00:41:00,424 --> 00:41:02,624
Fellas, kneel!

616
00:41:03,169 --> 00:41:05,420
People won't forget what you're doing here.

617
00:41:05,445 --> 00:41:06,861
Aim!

618
00:41:08,915 --> 00:41:10,748
They're gonna remember this,

619
00:41:10,867 --> 00:41:13,668
and they're gonna remember the Alamo.

620
00:41:13,753 --> 00:41:15,119
Remember the Alamo.

621
00:41:15,205 --> 00:41:17,705
(all) Remember the Alamo!

622
00:41:17,791 --> 00:41:19,073
Remember the Alamo!

623
00:41:19,175 --> 00:41:21,175
(all) Remember the Alamo!

624
00:41:21,261 --> 00:41:22,593
Fire!

625
00:41:22,712 --> 00:41:25,633
[gunfire]

626
00:41:31,271 --> 00:41:33,271
[man groaning]

627
00:41:37,311 --> 00:41:39,111
left, right, left, right, left, right...

628
00:41:39,136 --> 00:41:41,238
(man) Houston needs to cease wasting time

629
00:41:41,263 --> 00:41:42,891
with these exercises
and march us to Goliad,

630
00:41:42,916 --> 00:41:46,568
otherwise we'll have a repetition of Alamo.

631
00:41:46,670 --> 00:41:51,239
I do believe if President
Burnet knew of our situation,

632
00:41:52,735 --> 00:41:54,151
it'd be a different story.

633
00:41:54,176 --> 00:41:56,894
- Mm-hmm.
- Again, Sergeant. Again.

634
00:41:57,012 --> 00:41:59,273
Mosley Baker... suggestion?

635
00:41:59,298 --> 00:42:00,830
(Lamar) Sir!

636
00:42:01,217 --> 00:42:02,633
Private Lamar...

637
00:42:02,752 --> 00:42:04,635
I volunteered to fight for Texas,

638
00:42:04,754 --> 00:42:06,953
not march in a damned Easter parade.

639
00:42:07,056 --> 00:42:08,639
Is that right?

640
00:42:10,360 --> 00:42:13,694
Private Lamar, report here now!

641
00:42:14,280 --> 00:42:17,164
We will not tolerate insolent behavior!

642
00:42:19,474 --> 00:42:22,068
This is Mirabeau Lamar.

643
00:42:22,171 --> 00:42:27,124
He's secretly circulating a
petition to remove Houston.

644
00:42:27,209 --> 00:42:29,009
Sir?

645
00:42:29,094 --> 00:42:32,212
Private Lamar... please.

646
00:42:37,186 --> 00:42:38,352
You may sit.

647
00:42:43,192 --> 00:42:48,729
Private Lamar, we had a crisis
with our gutless commander,

648
00:42:48,814 --> 00:42:51,732
and we understand you are of a like mind.

649
00:42:54,153 --> 00:42:56,069
We need to get a urgent message

650
00:42:56,155 --> 00:42:59,272
to Secretary of War Rusk.

651
00:42:59,375 --> 00:43:00,707
Can you do that?

652
00:43:04,630 --> 00:43:07,047
They may not know how to march,

653
00:43:07,132 --> 00:43:11,635
but trust me, they know how to argue.

654
00:43:11,754 --> 00:43:16,790
Colonel Seguin, despite
our poor marching abilities,

655
00:43:16,892 --> 00:43:19,643
take comfort in knowing that
the men's hatred for Santa Anna

656
00:43:19,762 --> 00:43:20,894
binds us together.

657
00:43:29,822 --> 00:43:32,823
And so does their hatred for Sam Houston.

658
00:43:37,580 --> 00:43:38,912
(man) The horses are tuckered.

659
00:43:38,998 --> 00:43:41,248
There's a water hole
right around that bend.

660
00:43:41,333 --> 00:43:43,584
♪ ♪

661
00:43:43,669 --> 00:43:46,486
Charmaine could use a nice
drink and a good graze,

662
00:43:46,589 --> 00:43:48,464
couldn't you, old girl?

663
00:43:48,489 --> 00:43:50,267
Captain, it seems like you love that horse

664
00:43:50,315 --> 00:43:53,566
more than you do your wife.

665
00:43:53,629 --> 00:43:56,213
Hey, Deaf, who's a better mount:

666
00:43:56,298 --> 00:43:59,132
your wife or your horse?

667
00:43:59,218 --> 00:44:00,801
A horse.

668
00:44:00,886 --> 00:44:02,936
He sure does love that horse.

669
00:44:03,022 --> 00:44:04,187
I see; you're having a nice jest

670
00:44:04,306 --> 00:44:07,007
at the expense of my impairment.

671
00:44:07,109 --> 00:44:09,693
The good thing is I don't need
to hear no disparaging nonsense

672
00:44:09,812 --> 00:44:11,612
from the likes of you.

673
00:44:11,697 --> 00:44:13,146
You have something to say that matters,

674
00:44:13,232 --> 00:44:15,699
you best say to my fast.

675
00:44:15,818 --> 00:44:17,183
That's all right, Captain.

676
00:44:17,286 --> 00:44:21,288
No sense in getting all hot and bothered.

677
00:44:21,373 --> 00:44:23,523
Hey, I'm just wondering who bucks harder.

678
00:44:23,626 --> 00:44:25,242
[laughter]

679
00:44:25,327 --> 00:44:28,161
- What'd he say?
- Nothing.

680
00:44:32,835 --> 00:44:35,836
[indistinct chatter]

681
00:44:39,892 --> 00:44:41,708
(Baker) The Union's impositions

682
00:44:41,810 --> 00:44:45,762
have negative repercussions
for the individuals of Texas.

683
00:44:45,848 --> 00:44:50,017
Texas must be a sovereign nation.

684
00:44:50,102 --> 00:44:52,152
President Jackson
supports western expansion

685
00:44:52,237 --> 00:44:53,654
all the way to the coast.

686
00:44:53,739 --> 00:44:54,988
Then why doesn't he send his troops?

687
00:44:55,074 --> 00:44:56,740
Because this way,

688
00:44:56,859 --> 00:45:00,610
Jackson is free to let
Texas into the Union,

689
00:45:00,696 --> 00:45:03,507
and lead a clear, militaristic path

690
00:45:03,532 --> 00:45:05,365
all the way to California.

691
00:45:05,450 --> 00:45:08,702
Your blind ignorance
never ceases to amaze me.

692
00:45:08,787 --> 00:45:10,937
Old Hickory is bound by treaty.

693
00:45:11,039 --> 00:45:13,206
He can't just invade Mexico

694
00:45:13,292 --> 00:45:16,159
and invite the likes of
the Spaniards and the French

695
00:45:16,245 --> 00:45:18,128
and the crusty Brits to intervene.

696
00:45:18,247 --> 00:45:20,463
This is different, gentlemen.

697
00:45:20,582 --> 00:45:21,998
This is Texas.

698
00:45:22,084 --> 00:45:24,417
- Hey, Texas is part of Mexico.
- Yeah.

699
00:45:24,503 --> 00:45:26,286
What do you think we're fighting for, huh?

700
00:45:26,388 --> 00:45:29,122
Yeah, but this is where
you're wrong, Colonel Seguin.

701
00:45:29,224 --> 00:45:34,394
With Houston as our general,
we don't do much fighting.

702
00:45:44,173 --> 00:45:46,256
(Houston) Robert Knowles,

703
00:45:46,341 --> 00:45:49,009
you're not hiding from
your general, are you?

704
00:45:49,094 --> 00:45:50,227
(Knowles) [laughs]

705
00:45:50,345 --> 00:45:54,064
No, no, sir, I was just...

706
00:45:54,183 --> 00:45:56,733
Yes, sir, I was trying to hide
from you, General Houston, sir.

707
00:45:56,852 --> 00:45:58,652
I... yes.

708
00:45:58,737 --> 00:46:01,188
I have my eye on you.

709
00:46:01,273 --> 00:46:03,607
You rangering now?

710
00:46:03,692 --> 00:46:06,076
He prefers it to the firing squad.

711
00:46:06,101 --> 00:46:07,650
How's he doing?

712
00:46:07,763 --> 00:46:08,929
Passable.

713
00:46:09,014 --> 00:46:10,731
Ain't tried to run off.

714
00:46:10,816 --> 00:46:12,065
I'm with Vern.

715
00:46:12,151 --> 00:46:13,734
I say we shoot him.

716
00:46:13,819 --> 00:46:15,852
- I tried, General.
- He did.

717
00:46:15,938 --> 00:46:17,571
Be happy to try again.

718
00:46:17,656 --> 00:46:18,905
[laughter]

719
00:46:18,991 --> 00:46:20,607
We let him ride with us.

720
00:46:20,692 --> 00:46:22,826
We didn't know what else to do with him.

721
00:46:22,945 --> 00:46:25,145
(Houston) Robert, what qualities
do you possess to commend

722
00:46:25,247 --> 00:46:26,646
you for a pardon?

723
00:46:26,749 --> 00:46:28,698
He don't got no good qualities.

724
00:46:28,784 --> 00:46:30,083
Hell no.

725
00:46:30,169 --> 00:46:31,835
Qualities, sir... qualities.

726
00:46:31,954 --> 00:46:35,505
Well, I like this part of
the country a whole lot.

727
00:46:35,530 --> 00:46:38,364
I like the air around here.

728
00:46:38,389 --> 00:46:39,554
I like... I do.

729
00:46:39,579 --> 00:46:41,155
I like breathing it in, and then,

730
00:46:41,180 --> 00:46:43,213
I like sleeping under the stars as well.

731
00:46:43,298 --> 00:46:46,166
And, oh, I like breathing the
air while I'm sleeping under...

732
00:46:46,191 --> 00:46:47,654
Knowles,

733
00:46:47,679 --> 00:46:50,193
can't you think of anything
good to say about yourself?

734
00:46:53,225 --> 00:46:54,941
No.

735
00:46:56,979 --> 00:46:59,846
Damn it, I promise you, General Houston,

736
00:46:59,948 --> 00:47:03,116
I do not care about nobody but myself.

737
00:47:03,202 --> 00:47:07,070
I am bull-headed, and
I'm ornery as a snake.

738
00:47:07,156 --> 00:47:08,622
Ornery?

739
00:47:11,243 --> 00:47:12,192
Ornery's good.

740
00:47:12,294 --> 00:47:14,194
Yep.

741
00:47:14,496 --> 00:47:17,030
Ornery's not bad for rangering company.

742
00:47:17,115 --> 00:47:19,165
- Ornery!
- Ornery.

743
00:47:19,251 --> 00:47:20,867
Right? Let's ride out, boys.

744
00:47:20,952 --> 00:47:23,086
Vern's the orneriest son of a bitch I know.

745
00:47:23,205 --> 00:47:26,006
Yes, he is.

746
00:47:26,091 --> 00:47:27,340
Ornery.

747
00:47:29,378 --> 00:47:30,460
♪ ♪

748
00:47:30,545 --> 00:47:31,878
Whoo!

749
00:47:35,350 --> 00:47:40,261
_

750
00:47:42,224 --> 00:47:44,024
You gonna cook them taters

751
00:47:44,109 --> 00:47:48,462
or make a necklace out of
'em to wear with your skirt?

752
00:48:04,796 --> 00:48:07,797
I bet you dyspepsia is not unknown to you.

753
00:48:07,916 --> 00:48:09,735
Can't say I know him.

754
00:48:11,119 --> 00:48:13,320
Oh.

755
00:48:13,505 --> 00:48:15,305
You know what, Hays?

756
00:48:15,424 --> 00:48:17,841
You remind me of my big brother Samuel.

757
00:48:17,926 --> 00:48:20,093
I'm chagrined by the
notion of any resemblance

758
00:48:20,178 --> 00:48:23,313
to myself and any pack
member of the Wallace species.

759
00:48:23,432 --> 00:48:25,181
Well, don't get the big head on me.

760
00:48:25,267 --> 00:48:28,401
You don't look more alike
than me and a mule's ass.

761
00:48:28,487 --> 00:48:29,969
Well, dead ringers, then...

762
00:48:30,072 --> 00:48:31,571
uncanny.

763
00:48:33,191 --> 00:48:35,408
Sammy's got a way about him.

764
00:48:35,494 --> 00:48:37,643
Horse sense, I guess you'd call it.

765
00:48:37,746 --> 00:48:39,746
I see a lot of him in you.

766
00:48:45,954 --> 00:48:48,121
This can stand to stew a bit yet.

767
00:48:52,127 --> 00:48:53,793
When we was growing up,

768
00:48:53,879 --> 00:48:57,097
Sammy saved my sorry butt more than once.

769
00:48:57,182 --> 00:48:58,798
Ward off the bullies, did he?

770
00:48:58,884 --> 00:49:00,717
Oh, hell no... made me whoop 'em.

771
00:49:00,802 --> 00:49:03,219
If I hadn't, he'da whooped me worse.

772
00:49:03,305 --> 00:49:05,105
I sense our kinship.

773
00:49:05,190 --> 00:49:08,775
Hey, you sass me all you want
with that highbrow blather,

774
00:49:08,860 --> 00:49:12,145
but I am paying you one
hell of a compliment.

775
00:49:13,865 --> 00:49:17,183
If your brother's half the man you are,

776
00:49:17,285 --> 00:49:19,235
we're gonna be good friends.

777
00:49:19,321 --> 00:49:22,038
[laughs]

778
00:49:22,157 --> 00:49:23,907
Taters could've used another five minutes

779
00:49:23,992 --> 00:49:26,126
on the coals.

780
00:49:30,215 --> 00:49:34,367
[birds squawking]

781
00:49:34,469 --> 00:49:37,370
[foreboding music]

782
00:49:37,472 --> 00:49:45,478
♪ ♪

783
00:49:55,941 --> 00:49:57,824
Ah!

784
00:50:00,648 --> 00:50:02,230
[indistinct chatter]

785
00:50:02,304 --> 00:50:03,894
_

786
00:50:03,919 --> 00:50:05,452
(man) Careful with that.

787
00:50:05,500 --> 00:50:07,200
Those are the president's belongings.

788
00:50:07,285 --> 00:50:09,525
Hurry up. No time to waste.

789
00:50:14,376 --> 00:50:15,792
President Burnet?

790
00:50:15,877 --> 00:50:17,510
President Burnet is busy.

791
00:50:17,596 --> 00:50:18,928
I need to see the president.

792
00:50:19,047 --> 00:50:22,748
Santanistas just burned Bellville.

793
00:50:22,851 --> 00:50:24,133
(man) Señor, I said you can't come in.

794
00:50:24,219 --> 00:50:25,692
(Lamar) Mr. President,

795
00:50:25,717 --> 00:50:27,531
I'm here under urgent dispatch
of Colonel Mosley Baker.

796
00:50:27,556 --> 00:50:29,189
It is my duty to present this petition

797
00:50:29,274 --> 00:50:30,974
- from your rank and file.
- And you would be?

798
00:50:31,059 --> 00:50:33,889
Private Mirabeau Bonaparte
Lamar... Fairfield, Georgia, sir.

799
00:50:34,023 --> 00:50:35,028
Spit it out, boy.

800
00:50:35,113 --> 00:50:37,063
We got to go before Santa Anna gets here.

801
00:50:37,148 --> 00:50:38,982
Houston will not engage.

802
00:50:39,067 --> 00:50:41,150
Rusk, why won't your men meet the enemy?

803
00:50:41,236 --> 00:50:43,236
- 'Cause he's a damned coward.
- Houston may be many things,

804
00:50:43,321 --> 00:50:45,071
but a coward he is not.

805
00:50:45,156 --> 00:50:46,906
Then what in the name of
God is that man's soul?

806
00:50:46,992 --> 00:50:49,442
I presume General Houston
is picking his ground, sir.

807
00:50:49,544 --> 00:50:51,911
Forgive me Mister
Secretary, Mister President.

808
00:50:51,997 --> 00:50:54,080
I desperately insist you come to the front.

809
00:50:54,165 --> 00:50:55,948
I feel we face a mass desertion.

810
00:50:56,051 --> 00:50:57,383
Look around you, son.

811
00:50:57,469 --> 00:51:00,286
The Santanistas are half
a day's ride from here.

812
00:51:00,388 --> 00:51:04,123
We've abandoned the capitol,
and I'm on the run again.

813
00:51:04,226 --> 00:51:05,475
Now, if I am captured or killed,

814
00:51:05,594 --> 00:51:07,793
this rebellion is finished.

815
00:51:07,896 --> 00:51:10,096
Francisco, we're on our way

816
00:51:10,181 --> 00:51:13,799
to New Orleans to set up
a provisional government.

817
00:51:13,902 --> 00:51:16,819
Now, Rusk, you go tell
Houston that both his troops

818
00:51:16,938 --> 00:51:18,938
and the enemy are laughing him to scorn.

819
00:51:19,024 --> 00:51:21,991
He must fight, or I'll
find someone who will.

820
00:51:22,210 --> 00:51:23,576
Yes, sir.

821
00:51:23,678 --> 00:51:26,012
- Francisco, let's go!
- Yes, sir.

822
00:51:26,097 --> 00:51:28,431
(Burnet) Get everyone out
before the Mexicans get here!

823
00:51:28,550 --> 00:51:30,916
(Rusk) All right, young man,
I want to hear every detail.

824
00:51:31,019 --> 00:51:34,187
(Lamar) A petition signed by each
and every man under General Houston

825
00:51:34,272 --> 00:51:36,189
to relieve him of his command...

826
00:51:39,644 --> 00:51:47,650
♪ ♪

827
00:52:04,586 --> 00:52:06,085
[goat bleats]

828
00:52:08,256 --> 00:52:11,957
(Lorca) Lucifer himself is
risen from the bowels of Hades

829
00:52:12,060 --> 00:52:13,810
to tear the turgid flesh

830
00:52:13,928 --> 00:52:17,013
off the bones of all Mexicans...

831
00:52:17,098 --> 00:52:19,315
pluck their eyes and eat their livers,

832
00:52:19,434 --> 00:52:21,150
till their wretched screams

833
00:52:21,269 --> 00:52:25,154
for the angel of death
deafen this godforsaken Earth!

834
00:52:25,273 --> 00:52:27,306
Who are you?

835
00:52:27,409 --> 00:52:30,076
(Lorca) I am the punishment,

836
00:52:30,161 --> 00:52:32,862
here to spite every jumping bean lubricano,

837
00:52:32,947 --> 00:52:36,199
man, woman, and child
from the Texas plains!

838
00:52:36,284 --> 00:52:39,502
This is war, not a crusade.

839
00:52:42,207 --> 00:52:44,957
Had you witnessed the
abominations at the Alamo

840
00:52:45,043 --> 00:52:47,343
and Goliad, you'd think differently.

841
00:52:47,462 --> 00:52:48,928
Goliad?

842
00:52:49,013 --> 00:52:51,964
Damned crazy bastard, speak plain.

843
00:52:52,050 --> 00:52:55,518
They're all dead... murdered.

844
00:52:55,637 --> 00:53:00,056
300 slain... slaughtered after surrender.

845
00:53:00,141 --> 00:53:03,359
So much blood the air
turned to a crimson mist.

846
00:53:03,478 --> 00:53:05,111
Two of my Rangers boys were there.

847
00:53:05,196 --> 00:53:06,512
One had red hair.

848
00:53:06,614 --> 00:53:08,281
The other one rode a big black gelding.

849
00:53:08,366 --> 00:53:09,982
What of them?

850
00:53:10,068 --> 00:53:12,368
Got ambushed.

851
00:53:12,487 --> 00:53:15,071
Shot by so many bullets, shred the skin

852
00:53:15,156 --> 00:53:16,522
clean off their bodies...

853
00:53:16,624 --> 00:53:20,209
splintered their skulls beyond recognition.

854
00:53:20,328 --> 00:53:22,378
All the bodies lay as they fell,

855
00:53:22,497 --> 00:53:27,250
left to rot for the
buzzards and the maggots!

856
00:53:27,735 --> 00:53:29,485
By what right do you have to do this?

857
00:53:29,570 --> 00:53:31,570
I claim the ancient right

858
00:53:31,656 --> 00:53:35,658
by my own death denied
and my brethren butchered!

859
00:53:35,743 --> 00:53:37,877
Your account of Goliad...

860
00:53:37,902 --> 00:53:40,686
I'll need more than a lunatic's word.

861
00:53:40,711 --> 00:53:43,851
I answer to neither man nor God.

862
00:53:44,185 --> 00:53:47,103
There's Chupaldo, Santa Anna's courier.

863
00:53:47,221 --> 00:53:50,139
Why don't you ask him for his account?

864
00:53:50,224 --> 00:53:56,028
Best make haste... fresh
dispatch from Santa Anna himself.

865
00:53:56,114 --> 00:53:58,481
I am a servant to Lucifer!

866
00:53:58,566 --> 00:54:01,701
Death to all brown-skinned Mexican demons!

867
00:54:01,786 --> 00:54:04,120
[flies buzzing]

868
00:54:12,719 --> 00:54:14,976
_

869
00:54:15,101 --> 00:54:18,102
[indistinct chatter]

870
00:54:18,569 --> 00:54:22,654
[woman crying]

871
00:54:27,095 --> 00:54:33,248
Don Antonio, Burnet has just
escaped with his hand rush.

872
00:54:33,351 --> 00:54:35,718
We were only moments too late.

873
00:54:35,803 --> 00:54:37,720
The bite of the flames,

874
00:54:37,805 --> 00:54:39,722
the sting of the smoke...

875
00:54:39,807 --> 00:54:40,723
don't you feel it?

876
00:54:40,808 --> 00:54:42,691
Feel what, sir?

877
00:54:42,777 --> 00:54:44,259
Death.

878
00:54:44,362 --> 00:54:46,145
Are you hot, Almonte?

879
00:54:46,230 --> 00:54:47,897
Aye.

880
00:54:47,982 --> 00:54:49,365
The flesh of victory

881
00:54:49,450 --> 00:54:51,617
and the cries of the dying...

882
00:54:51,736 --> 00:54:54,703
does it not excite you?

883
00:54:54,789 --> 00:54:57,990
What an ordinary man
feels as pain or revulsion

884
00:54:58,075 --> 00:55:01,377
a real soldier must
learn to feel as pleasure.

885
00:55:05,216 --> 00:55:09,752
This is war,

886
00:55:09,837 --> 00:55:13,923
and the truth is, we enjoy it.

887
00:55:14,008 --> 00:55:17,343
[people screaming]

888
00:55:17,428 --> 00:55:20,930
Our enemies are rabble.

889
00:55:21,015 --> 00:55:26,101
The public's gratitude is uncertain.

890
00:55:26,187 --> 00:55:30,105
The politicians: fickle at best.

891
00:55:32,827 --> 00:55:35,143
A moment like this one...

892
00:55:35,246 --> 00:55:40,866
victory gives purpose
to all our sacrifices...

893
00:55:43,254 --> 00:55:44,954
our suffering.

894
00:55:49,710 --> 00:55:52,628
[dramatic music]

895
00:55:52,713 --> 00:56:00,719
♪ ♪

896
00:56:01,806 --> 00:56:03,574
[woman screams]

897
00:56:05,393 --> 00:56:06,806
Jose.

898
00:56:08,863 --> 00:56:10,362
Madam, come with me. Come.

899
00:56:10,481 --> 00:56:12,374
Come. Come. Come. Come. Come.

900
00:56:20,241 --> 00:56:23,859
(Karnes) There is little
more I can add, Mrs. Fincham,

901
00:56:23,961 --> 00:56:29,197
excepting that Truett and
Yancey accounted for themselves

902
00:56:29,300 --> 00:56:32,868
in this campaign with...

903
00:56:33,770 --> 00:56:36,003
what's the fancy word for<i> cojones?</i>

904
00:56:36,106 --> 00:56:37,772
I reckon "valor" is pretty good.

905
00:56:37,858 --> 00:56:39,607
With valor.

906
00:56:41,845 --> 00:56:44,379
You ought to be proud of your son,

907
00:56:44,464 --> 00:56:47,799
as the Rangers hold them in highest regard.

908
00:56:50,137 --> 00:56:51,970
Sincerely, H. Barns.

909
00:56:55,642 --> 00:56:56,942
They was good boys.

910
00:57:00,147 --> 00:57:02,648
Now, read that all back
to me from the start.

911
00:57:02,766 --> 00:57:04,433
It ought to be suitable.

912
00:57:07,438 --> 00:57:09,154
Youse hungry, ain't you?

913
00:57:09,273 --> 00:57:11,106
So hungry my belly button's
gnawing on my backbone.

914
00:57:11,191 --> 00:57:12,524
Go ahead.

915
00:57:18,693 --> 00:57:20,626
(man) That crazy old coot.

916
00:57:20,651 --> 00:57:21,851
I ain't seen nothing like him in
the good lord's Christian world.

917
00:57:21,953 --> 00:57:23,118
Did you see his eyes?

918
00:57:23,204 --> 00:57:25,037
- His... they were dead.
- Oh, yeah.

919
00:57:25,122 --> 00:57:28,457
Just dead... like chunks of black coal.

920
00:57:28,964 --> 00:57:30,546
I don't recall the bible talking

921
00:57:30,571 --> 00:57:31,987
about a demon of his ilk.

922
00:57:32,012 --> 00:57:33,461
Lorca.

923
00:57:33,564 --> 00:57:36,298
- What?
- Lorca.

924
00:57:36,400 --> 00:57:38,286
Lorca?

925
00:57:38,654 --> 00:57:45,636
What is that, some
Injun name for Beelzebub?

926
00:57:45,734 --> 00:57:48,585
(Anderson) It's Cayuga legend.

927
00:57:48,616 --> 00:57:51,617
In ancient times, there
was an Atikapan warrior

928
00:57:51,698 --> 00:57:56,918
who was killed in battle without honor,

929
00:57:57,004 --> 00:57:59,454
and when his spirit rose,

930
00:57:59,539 --> 00:58:02,841
it peeled off the skin
of his barbarian enemies,

931
00:58:02,959 --> 00:58:07,929
and the sun burned them until...

932
00:58:08,015 --> 00:58:12,050
their insides were crisp.

933
00:58:12,135 --> 00:58:14,874
Sweet Jesus, that's what he did.

934
00:58:16,456 --> 00:58:19,257
All right, just so you fellows know,

935
00:58:19,376 --> 00:58:21,610
we chance on his like again,

936
00:58:21,712 --> 00:58:25,380
I will likely soil myself straight away.

937
00:58:25,465 --> 00:58:28,350
Oh, that's more than likely in your case.

938
00:58:28,435 --> 00:58:31,886
I'm not at all sure this
rangering business suits me.

939
00:58:37,394 --> 00:58:40,145
If'n these jackasses won't say it, I will.

940
00:58:40,330 --> 00:58:41,696
That lickspittle Knowles was right.

941
00:58:41,798 --> 00:58:43,698
Our cause is lost, damn it.

942
00:58:43,800 --> 00:58:46,718
The onliest thing we're gonna
find in Texas is our graves.

943
00:58:46,837 --> 00:58:49,304
Turn and run, huh? Is that it, Vern?

944
00:58:49,389 --> 00:58:53,508
Hell no. Turn, run, and fornicate.

945
00:58:53,593 --> 00:58:56,428
Texas is fine country, but Texican women...

946
00:58:56,513 --> 00:58:59,347
they're so ugly they'd back
a buzzard off a gut wagon.

947
00:58:59,433 --> 00:59:02,851
I'd sooner service a sow.

948
00:59:02,936 --> 00:59:04,719
I'd best get back to Paris.

949
00:59:04,821 --> 00:59:07,405
Ooh, Paris, huh? Paris.

950
00:59:07,524 --> 00:59:10,892
In Paris, the missies paint their faces

951
00:59:10,994 --> 00:59:15,747
like dolls, wear bodices,
make their teats spill out,

952
00:59:15,866 --> 00:59:19,284
and the clincer is, they perfume their quim

953
00:59:19,369 --> 00:59:22,036
to smell just like lilac.

954
00:59:22,122 --> 00:59:25,790
You are a sinner, Vern,
marked by a terrible stain.

955
00:59:25,876 --> 00:59:27,709
- Now, your British wench...
- Mm-hmm?

956
00:59:27,794 --> 00:59:29,294
She kind of fleshy...

957
00:59:29,479 --> 00:59:31,029
stinks a little when she sweats,

958
00:59:31,147 --> 00:59:34,699
and she gonna sweat
plenty when I'm riding her.

959
00:59:34,818 --> 00:59:38,403
Course, your best poke, now, in my opinion,

960
00:59:38,488 --> 00:59:40,154
is ports of call of Spain.

961
00:59:40,240 --> 00:59:41,539
Spain?

962
00:59:41,658 --> 00:59:42,707
You been to Spain too, huh?

963
00:59:42,826 --> 00:59:43,825
Don't interrupt.

964
00:59:43,910 --> 00:59:45,192
All right. Continue.

965
00:59:45,295 --> 00:59:48,713
Them skinny little dark-eyed gypsy girls

966
00:59:48,832 --> 00:59:52,250
twirl around on your
pecker like a butter churn.

967
00:59:55,088 --> 00:59:58,556
Yeah, well, you come near my sisters,

968
00:59:58,675 --> 01:00:02,760
and I will shoot your
lecherous ass graveyard-dead.

969
01:00:02,846 --> 01:00:06,047
And you best not so much
as glance at Rebecca,

970
01:00:06,149 --> 01:00:08,566
that sweet young thing
we rescued at Gonzales.

971
01:00:08,685 --> 01:00:11,986
I don't care one stringy
bean for that 7x9 gal.

972
01:00:16,743 --> 01:00:18,109
Come with me, kid.

973
01:00:18,194 --> 01:00:19,911
We'll catch a schooner out of New Orleans

974
01:00:20,030 --> 01:00:22,747
with some of my old swabbies.

975
01:00:22,866 --> 01:00:25,750
We ain't gonna do nothing
here but die young.

976
01:00:25,869 --> 01:00:28,753
[soft music]

977
01:00:28,872 --> 01:00:36,711
♪ ♪

978
01:00:36,796 --> 01:00:38,846
[people shouting]

979
01:00:38,932 --> 01:00:41,849
[lively music playing]

980
01:00:41,935 --> 01:00:49,941
♪ ♪

981
01:01:18,755 --> 01:01:25,960
♪ ♪

982
01:01:26,062 --> 01:01:28,513
[cheers and applause]

983
01:01:52,389 --> 01:01:54,973
[gunshot]

984
01:01:55,092 --> 01:01:57,026
Sir, it now seems unlikely
the Texans will prevail,

985
01:01:57,081 --> 01:01:58,761
_

986
01:01:58,792 --> 01:02:01,945
especially since Houston's at
odds with his officer corps.

987
01:02:02,016 --> 01:02:04,983
Damned Texans.

988
01:02:05,602 --> 01:02:07,318
Been at odds with them myself.

989
01:02:07,467 --> 01:02:09,894
So Mister President, should we advise

990
01:02:09,927 --> 01:02:14,212
the Texans to relieve
General Houston of Command?

991
01:02:14,744 --> 01:02:16,310
As long as I've lived,

992
01:02:16,413 --> 01:02:18,646
I've been a keen judge of horse flesh.

993
01:02:18,748 --> 01:02:21,533
What clenches it for me is
just staring in the horse's eyes

994
01:02:21,618 --> 01:02:24,586
and letting him tell me who he is.

995
01:02:24,671 --> 01:02:26,821
I first looked into Sam Houston's eyes

996
01:02:26,923 --> 01:02:29,424
at the Battle of Horseshoe.

997
01:02:29,509 --> 01:02:31,676
He was 19 years old...

998
01:02:31,795 --> 01:02:35,396
first on the line, first on the assault,

999
01:02:35,499 --> 01:02:38,233
first to be marked for death.

1000
01:02:38,335 --> 01:02:40,835
I did not propose to understand him,

1001
01:02:40,937 --> 01:02:44,239
but if there's a way to defeat Santa Anna,

1002
01:02:44,341 --> 01:02:47,942
the only man capable of
doing so is Sam Houston,

1003
01:02:48,144 --> 01:02:50,645
except for me, of course.

1004
01:02:50,947 --> 01:02:53,181
All right there, Charmaine.

1005
01:02:53,283 --> 01:02:55,116
Good night, girl.

1006
01:02:58,199 --> 01:02:59,865
[coughing]

1007
01:03:04,194 --> 01:03:08,062
God knows I wanted to
be wrong about Fannin.

1008
01:03:08,165 --> 01:03:09,531
Goldarn it.

1009
01:03:11,952 --> 01:03:12,951
Deaf...

1010
01:03:16,873 --> 01:03:18,790
I'm hungry for counsel.

1011
01:03:18,875 --> 01:03:20,592
I'd welcome yours.

1012
01:03:23,680 --> 01:03:25,313
Well, one thing Santa Anna's done...

1013
01:03:25,398 --> 01:03:28,349
he's let every Texian know
that to surrender means death.

1014
01:03:30,770 --> 01:03:33,821
Don't run from him no more.

1015
01:03:33,907 --> 01:03:35,156
Fight him like Comanches.

1016
01:03:35,242 --> 01:03:38,660
You stay close... so close
he can feel your breath.

1017
01:03:38,745 --> 01:03:42,697
You let him know you're always
there and he can't touch you.

1018
01:03:42,782 --> 01:03:46,751
Sooner or later, he's gonna
show you his tender underbelly,

1019
01:03:46,870 --> 01:03:48,620
and when he does,

1020
01:03:48,705 --> 01:03:50,905
you take that sword of yours
and you sink it to the hilt.

1021
01:03:51,007 --> 01:03:54,241
You slit him through and through.

1022
01:03:54,344 --> 01:03:57,629
Well, that's all well and good.

1023
01:03:57,714 --> 01:04:01,049
What about his other
generals and their armies?

1024
01:04:01,134 --> 01:04:04,302
Cut the head off the snake, the body dies.

1025
01:04:08,441 --> 01:04:10,091
[chuckles]

1026
01:04:10,193 --> 01:04:12,727
(man) How do you know this, Francisco?

1027
01:04:12,812 --> 01:04:14,696
(Francisco) I heard it from
President Burnet's own mouth.

1028
01:04:14,781 --> 01:04:17,365
He's fleeing to New Orleans
by way of Galveston Bay.

1029
01:04:17,450 --> 01:04:19,284
(Santa Anna) And Houston...

1030
01:04:19,402 --> 01:04:20,952
What is his position?

1031
01:04:21,071 --> 01:04:23,655
Somewhere west of the
Sabine River below Gonzales.

1032
01:04:23,740 --> 01:04:27,241
Rumors say that he's crazy
and his troops are mutinous.

1033
01:04:27,327 --> 01:04:29,610
Burnet ordered Houston
to meet you on the field.

1034
01:04:29,713 --> 01:04:32,613
(Santa Anna) That's
exactly where I want him.

1035
01:04:32,716 --> 01:04:35,116
We will divide the army
into multiple divisions

1036
01:04:35,218 --> 01:04:38,786
to pursue and destroy what's
left of the rebel army.

1037
01:04:38,888 --> 01:04:39,971
(Almonte) General,

1038
01:04:40,090 --> 01:04:42,056
if you will indulge me...

1039
01:04:42,142 --> 01:04:43,808
our many great victories

1040
01:04:43,927 --> 01:04:46,094
have been because we maintain
an overwhelming force.

1041
01:04:46,179 --> 01:04:48,629
His Excellency's strategy is brilliant.

1042
01:04:48,732 --> 01:04:50,765
Ha.

1043
01:04:50,850 --> 01:04:53,017
(Almonte) What about President Jackson?

1044
01:04:53,103 --> 01:04:55,770
How can we be certain
that he will not intervene?

1045
01:04:55,855 --> 01:05:02,143
(Santa Anna) Almonte, Old
Hickory hides behind treaties...

1046
01:05:02,245 --> 01:05:04,812
moves in shadows.

1047
01:05:04,914 --> 01:05:07,782
His stole Florida from
Spain and claims Texas

1048
01:05:07,867 --> 01:05:10,317
was part of the Louisiana Purchase.

1049
01:05:10,420 --> 01:05:14,989
Texas is the pathway to the Pacific.

1050
01:05:15,091 --> 01:05:18,126
Jackson wants it all...

1051
01:05:18,211 --> 01:05:22,263
all the way to California.

1052
01:05:22,349 --> 01:05:28,353
Francisco, I reward results.

1053
01:05:28,471 --> 01:05:30,772
Bring me news.

1054
01:05:30,857 --> 01:05:32,190
Yes, Your Excellency.

1055
01:05:32,308 --> 01:05:34,275
(Santa Anna) Get back to your president!

1056
01:05:37,397 --> 01:05:39,136
[gasps]

1057
01:05:44,904 --> 01:05:52,910
♪ ♪

1058
01:06:08,312 --> 01:06:11,313
[laughter]

1059
01:06:11,415 --> 01:06:14,232
[mysterious music]

1060
01:06:14,318 --> 01:06:22,324
♪ ♪

1061
01:06:49,269 --> 01:06:54,939
A woman with full, meaty arms.

1062
01:06:55,025 --> 01:06:56,741
I like that! [laughs]

1063
01:06:56,860 --> 01:06:58,826
Be careful, my friend.

1064
01:06:58,912 --> 01:07:02,143
She's the Presidente General's property.

1065
01:07:02,416 --> 01:07:04,299
Hey, I know you.

1066
01:07:04,384 --> 01:07:06,468
You are Manuel Flores.

1067
01:07:06,553 --> 01:07:08,970
It is me, Hector Ribaldo.

1068
01:07:09,056 --> 01:07:12,424
We played cards. Remember? I won.

1069
01:07:12,509 --> 01:07:13,925
I was proud to take your money

1070
01:07:14,011 --> 01:07:15,927
'cause you joined the filthy rebels.

1071
01:07:16,013 --> 01:07:17,211
You mistake me for someone else.

1072
01:07:17,314 --> 01:07:19,731
No. I am quite certain.

1073
01:07:19,850 --> 01:07:22,267
You are a traitorous spy.

1074
01:07:24,571 --> 01:07:25,974
[grunts]

1075
01:07:37,451 --> 01:07:39,951
Meet me back here tonight at
the changing of the night guard.

1076
01:07:40,037 --> 01:07:41,586
- Yes.
- I have vital news.

1077
01:07:41,705 --> 01:07:42,587
- Yes. All right.
- Go.

1078
01:07:42,706 --> 01:07:44,589
(man) For Mexico!

1079
01:07:44,708 --> 01:07:45,866
(man) Presidente...

1080
01:07:52,382 --> 01:07:55,383
[indistinct chatter]

1081
01:07:59,773 --> 01:08:01,036
[laughs]

1082
01:08:02,809 --> 01:08:05,060
Everybody pays Francisco.

1083
01:08:09,566 --> 01:08:11,566
[clucking]

1084
01:08:16,089 --> 01:08:17,538
You pay me.

1085
01:08:19,576 --> 01:08:21,709
You pay me.

1086
01:08:22,095 --> 01:08:24,679
The rebel Presidente Burnet pays me.

1087
01:08:24,764 --> 01:08:26,597
[laughs]

1088
01:08:26,716 --> 01:08:31,752
Even His Excellency Santa Anna himself.

1089
01:08:31,855 --> 01:08:35,256
Everyone pays me.

1090
01:08:35,358 --> 01:08:39,060
Soon, that pirate Houston will pay me too.

1091
01:08:39,145 --> 01:08:40,812
Whoa!

1092
01:08:50,073 --> 01:08:51,572
I almost pissed myself.

1093
01:08:51,658 --> 01:08:53,157
[laughs]

1094
01:08:55,745 --> 01:09:03,751
♪ ♪

1095
01:09:08,174 --> 01:09:09,173
Francisco.

1096
01:09:11,995 --> 01:09:13,027
Who's that?

1097
01:09:13,329 --> 01:09:14,495
[groans]

1098
01:09:16,599 --> 01:09:19,050
This is how Houston pays spies.

1099
01:09:23,473 --> 01:09:26,357
[birds chirping]

1100
01:09:26,476 --> 01:09:29,143
[man snoring]

1101
01:09:38,371 --> 01:09:43,157
[dramatic guitar flourish]

1102
01:09:43,242 --> 01:09:49,208
♪ ♪

1103
01:09:49,233 --> 01:09:50,636
Oh!

1104
01:09:52,001 --> 01:10:00,007
♪ ♪

1105
01:10:01,778 --> 01:10:03,661
Come on. [shushes]

1106
01:10:12,622 --> 01:10:13,621
Howdy.

1107
01:10:16,710 --> 01:10:19,427
♪ ♪

1108
01:10:19,529 --> 01:10:21,462
Come on, Ruthie! Let's get!

1109
01:10:21,548 --> 01:10:23,881
Got me a wrist cuff! Whoo-hoo!

1110
01:10:23,967 --> 01:10:26,713
(man) Mount up, you dang slowpoke!

1111
01:10:27,904 --> 01:10:30,955
Oh... oh, shit!

1112
01:10:31,074 --> 01:10:33,510
Forget the damned horse. We got to get!

1113
01:10:40,083 --> 01:10:42,834
My horse! They stole my horse.

1114
01:10:44,888 --> 01:10:46,536
[grunts]

1115
01:10:46,790 --> 01:10:49,441
(Wallace) It's a long walk to Goliad.

1116
01:10:54,681 --> 01:10:56,931
(Flores) Go. Go. Go.

1117
01:10:57,017 --> 01:10:59,467
Go east to Houston's army.

1118
01:10:59,553 --> 01:11:00,552
God bless you.

1119
01:11:00,637 --> 01:11:02,909
Look out for Comanches.

1120
01:11:06,977 --> 01:11:10,178
[indistinct chatter]

1121
01:11:10,280 --> 01:11:13,565
[men singing in Spanish]

1122
01:11:17,654 --> 01:11:20,348
Flores.

1123
01:11:20,991 --> 01:11:23,408
- We have no time.
- We go now.

1124
01:11:23,493 --> 01:11:26,722
I'd be better use to Texas staying here.

1125
01:11:27,964 --> 01:11:30,515
Hey, you're coming with me...

1126
01:11:30,733 --> 01:11:32,099
General Houston's orders.

1127
01:11:32,201 --> 01:11:34,151
I don't answer to him.

1128
01:11:36,789 --> 01:11:39,796
If you want to kill Santa
Anna, you will need this.

1129
01:11:41,961 --> 01:11:43,661
You may lose your life.

1130
01:11:43,746 --> 01:11:45,580
What life?

1131
01:11:45,665 --> 01:11:47,281
I'm a Negro born out of
punishment to my mammy,

1132
01:11:47,383 --> 01:11:50,134
growed up to be a whore.

1133
01:11:50,253 --> 01:11:53,554
Tell the general Santa Anna's
pursuing him personally.

1134
01:11:53,640 --> 01:11:55,172
It's an obsession.

1135
01:11:55,258 --> 01:11:56,924
Give him these.

1136
01:11:57,010 --> 01:11:58,092
He'll know. Be vigilant.

1137
01:11:58,177 --> 01:12:00,159
Be safe. Hurry.

1138
01:12:01,181 --> 01:12:02,514
(Flores) Get back before Santa Anna wakes.

1139
01:12:17,080 --> 01:12:22,083
(Wallace) Sticks in my craw... them
trash got off with my wrist cuff.

1140
01:12:22,202 --> 01:12:23,751
You're out a trinket.

1141
01:12:23,870 --> 01:12:25,870
I'm on foot. All right.

1142
01:12:25,955 --> 01:12:28,956
That was a blooded thoroughbred
those wastrels took.

1143
01:12:29,342 --> 01:12:31,041
Raised him from a colt, I did.

1144
01:12:31,144 --> 01:12:32,309
That's why you got your mind

1145
01:12:32,395 --> 01:12:34,478
set on walking all the way to Goliad?

1146
01:12:34,564 --> 01:12:35,896
Do I have a choice?

1147
01:12:36,015 --> 01:12:37,431
And that was no trinket, hard case.

1148
01:12:37,517 --> 01:12:39,350
It was a precious family
heirloom made by my pa

1149
01:12:39,435 --> 01:12:41,519
for me and my brother.

1150
01:12:47,610 --> 01:12:50,194
[soft music]

1151
01:12:50,279 --> 01:12:59,336
♪ ♪

1152
01:12:59,422 --> 01:13:01,338
Still damp.

1153
01:13:01,424 --> 01:13:02,757
She's bleeding out.

1154
01:13:02,875 --> 01:13:04,041
Pissant she-devil bitch...

1155
01:13:04,127 --> 01:13:05,743
I hope so.

1156
01:13:05,845 --> 01:13:13,851
♪ ♪

1157
01:13:22,028 --> 01:13:25,029
[flies buzzing]

1158
01:13:28,067 --> 01:13:30,201
Psst! Psst! Psst!

1159
01:13:30,286 --> 01:13:31,402
Come on!

1160
01:13:34,909 --> 01:13:36,208
(Hays) You got your wish.

1161
01:13:36,242 --> 01:13:37,825
(Wallace) She wearing my wrist cuff?

1162
01:13:39,929 --> 01:13:41,745
No.

1163
01:13:41,848 --> 01:13:44,849
Pissant bitch.

1164
01:13:44,934 --> 01:13:47,768
You sure you don't want a ride?

1165
01:13:47,887 --> 01:13:50,555
I told you; two grown
men can't ride double.

1166
01:13:50,640 --> 01:13:52,106
It ain't dignified.

1167
01:13:52,225 --> 01:13:55,943
Oh, you want dignity or blisters?

1168
01:13:56,062 --> 01:13:57,228
Come on. Yah.

1169
01:14:04,784 --> 01:14:11,612
_

1170
01:14:13,129 --> 01:14:16,681
[dramatic music]

1171
01:14:16,783 --> 01:14:19,634
[all shouting]

1172
01:14:19,752 --> 01:14:22,553
Comanches! Comanches!

1173
01:14:22,639 --> 01:14:24,138
My rifle!

1174
01:14:24,257 --> 01:14:27,725
[all shouting]

1175
01:14:27,810 --> 01:14:30,895
(Houston) Hold your fire!

1176
01:14:30,980 --> 01:14:32,296
Hold your fire.

1177
01:14:32,398 --> 01:14:33,931
Oh, no, no, no, no.

1178
01:14:34,017 --> 01:14:35,566
I'm gonna be massacred by Comanches.

1179
01:14:35,652 --> 01:14:36,984
Shit, they ain't gonna take me alive.

1180
01:14:37,103 --> 01:14:38,819
Son of a bitch, let's open up on 'em!

1181
01:14:38,938 --> 01:14:40,855
(Houston) You'll follow orders!

1182
01:14:40,940 --> 01:14:44,775
[all shouting]

1183
01:14:53,036 --> 01:14:56,704
[speaking native language]

1184
01:14:59,759 --> 01:15:01,505
(Anderson) [speaking native language]

1185
01:15:10,603 --> 01:15:12,687
Fire on me if we fall dead.

1186
01:15:17,677 --> 01:15:19,176
Anderson talks Injun?

1187
01:15:19,278 --> 01:15:21,028
You just figured that out?

1188
01:15:21,147 --> 01:15:23,781
I thought he was kidnapped
by 'em when he was a boy.

1189
01:15:23,866 --> 01:15:26,517
You can smell the stinking savage on him.

1190
01:15:26,819 --> 01:15:28,964
Steady.

1191
01:16:03,272 --> 01:16:04,254
Tell him I'm a chieftain.

1192
01:16:04,357 --> 01:16:07,758
- He's aware.
- Good.

1193
01:16:07,860 --> 01:16:09,977
Tell him to kill me.

1194
01:16:10,062 --> 01:16:11,228
I don't think that's a good idea

1195
01:16:11,314 --> 01:16:13,898
with me standing next to you and all.

1196
01:16:13,983 --> 01:16:15,766
Go ahead.

1197
01:16:15,868 --> 01:16:17,735
Kill me,

1198
01:16:17,820 --> 01:16:21,989
if you want war the likes
the Comanches have never seen.

1199
01:16:22,074 --> 01:16:26,076
My death brings Yankee
soldiers like buffalo herds.

1200
01:16:26,162 --> 01:16:28,946
The croaking raven doth bellow for revenge.

1201
01:16:29,048 --> 01:16:31,114
Shakespeare does not
translate into Comanche.

1202
01:16:31,217 --> 01:16:32,249
[grunts]

1203
01:16:34,253 --> 01:16:41,455
[speaking native language]

1204
01:17:04,033 --> 01:17:06,417
He said that the Cherokee
call you the Raven,

1205
01:17:06,502 --> 01:17:09,119
but the Comanche call you Wild Turkey

1206
01:17:09,205 --> 01:17:12,256
because you drape
yourself in foolish colors

1207
01:17:12,341 --> 01:17:15,586
and you lose your head
when the coyote come.

1208
01:17:15,611 --> 01:17:17,277
What the hell they saying?

1209
01:17:17,363 --> 01:17:19,162
You'd prefer not knowing.

1210
01:17:19,248 --> 01:17:20,697
I would.

1211
01:17:20,783 --> 01:17:22,165
[shrieks]

1212
01:17:22,251 --> 01:17:24,785
[all shrieking]

1213
01:17:29,592 --> 01:17:34,178
[speaking native language]

1214
01:17:38,534 --> 01:17:40,818
If the Mexicans don't kill you, he will.

1215
01:17:43,506 --> 01:17:45,556
[shrieks]

1216
01:17:45,641 --> 01:17:47,558
[all shrieking]

1217
01:17:47,643 --> 01:17:48,903
Huh!

1218
01:17:59,271 --> 01:18:03,023
He's hardly 16 and he's already
got two scalps on his lance.

1219
01:18:03,109 --> 01:18:04,908
Friend of yours?

1220
01:18:04,994 --> 01:18:06,143
His name's Yellow Knife.

1221
01:18:06,245 --> 01:18:08,012
He's my son.

1222
01:18:18,656 --> 01:18:20,539
First wagon sets that side of the line!

1223
01:18:20,658 --> 01:18:23,125
Single file all the way to Nueces River!

1224
01:18:23,211 --> 01:18:26,579
[indistinct chatter]

1225
01:18:26,664 --> 01:18:29,582
[dramatic music]

1226
01:18:29,667 --> 01:18:37,673
♪ ♪

1227
01:18:43,231 --> 01:18:44,814
(man) Make sure of your spokes.

1228
01:18:44,899 --> 01:18:46,599
Make sure your water
barrels is full to the hilt!

1229
01:18:46,684 --> 01:18:49,068
We pull out for the [inaudible] in an hour!

1230
01:18:49,187 --> 01:18:51,020
You ain't ready, you're on your own!

1231
01:18:51,105 --> 01:18:53,189
(man) The Santanistas are killing everyone!

1232
01:18:53,274 --> 01:18:54,190
Flee for your lives!

1233
01:18:54,275 --> 01:18:56,025
Make that a 1/2 hour!

1234
01:18:56,110 --> 01:18:57,576
Let's go! Come on! Come on!

1235
01:18:57,695 --> 01:19:00,613
Go! Go!

1236
01:19:00,698 --> 01:19:02,281
Go!

1237
01:19:02,366 --> 01:19:04,166
They're coming!

1238
01:19:04,252 --> 01:19:05,701
Yah! Yah!

1239
01:19:05,786 --> 01:19:06,702
[horses whinny]

1240
01:19:06,787 --> 01:19:09,922
♪ ♪

1241
01:19:10,041 --> 01:19:11,207
(Pauline Wykoff) Everyone's skidaddling.

1242
01:19:11,292 --> 01:19:13,742
We're a long cry from Saint Louis.

1243
01:19:13,845 --> 01:19:16,178
(James Wykoff) Took everything
we had to get us this far.

1244
01:19:16,264 --> 01:19:17,847
Whoa.

1245
01:19:17,932 --> 01:19:21,116
There ain't nothing for us back home.

1246
01:19:21,219 --> 01:19:22,718
I told you the day we left,

1247
01:19:22,803 --> 01:19:25,187
I'd follow you to the ends of the Earth.

1248
01:19:25,273 --> 01:19:26,722
Well, this just might be it.

1249
01:19:29,060 --> 01:19:30,793
(Pauline Wykoff) Should
we turn and head back?

1250
01:19:35,800 --> 01:19:37,466
(man) No refunds!

1251
01:19:37,552 --> 01:19:40,803
Yes, sir; I'm a tracking
impresario Buckley.

1252
01:19:40,888 --> 01:19:44,023
And you're tracking me.
What can I do for you?

1253
01:19:44,142 --> 01:19:46,725
No refunds... as I've stated.

1254
01:19:46,811 --> 01:19:48,561
Yes, sir.

1255
01:19:48,646 --> 01:19:49,862
I'm looking to...

1256
01:19:49,981 --> 01:19:53,649
interested in a land grant.

1257
01:19:53,800 --> 01:19:55,911
With everyone leaving, why are you here?

1258
01:19:55,936 --> 01:19:58,687
- You running from the law?
- No, sir.

1259
01:19:58,773 --> 01:20:01,690
I'm interested in making a fresh start,

1260
01:20:01,776 --> 01:20:04,059
and getting some good land,

1261
01:20:04,161 --> 01:20:09,398
and now, I understand that the Mexican army

1262
01:20:09,500 --> 01:20:13,669
is driving all the Americans out.

1263
01:20:13,754 --> 01:20:16,088
Honest settlers have nothing to fear.

1264
01:20:16,207 --> 01:20:19,792
President Santa Anna
protects all legal landowners.

1265
01:20:19,877 --> 01:20:21,043
It's the thieving squatters

1266
01:20:21,128 --> 01:20:23,128
and revolutionaries that get shot.

1267
01:20:23,214 --> 01:20:24,797
I see.

1268
01:20:24,882 --> 01:20:26,682
Do you sweat allegiance
to the Republic of Mexico?

1269
01:20:26,767 --> 01:20:29,885
Yes, sir. For 6¢ an acre, I surely do.

1270
01:20:32,139 --> 01:20:35,757
I can grant 170 acres for farming,

1271
01:20:35,860 --> 01:20:38,977
but no whiskey brewing, gun
running, tobacco smuggling,

1272
01:20:39,063 --> 01:20:40,429
or frontier riff-raffing.

1273
01:20:40,531 --> 01:20:42,147
Oh, no, sir. I mean, yes, sir.

1274
01:20:42,233 --> 01:20:44,733
By law, improvements must be made timely,

1275
01:20:44,819 --> 01:20:46,952
but you've been shot in
the flanks with good luck.

1276
01:20:47,071 --> 01:20:49,104
There's a property
cleared with a sturdy cabin

1277
01:20:49,206 --> 01:20:50,873
on it ready to farm.

1278
01:20:50,958 --> 01:20:53,709
I can let you have it for 7 1/2¢ an acre.

1279
01:20:53,794 --> 01:20:55,377
You can pay on time, cash or trade.

1280
01:20:55,463 --> 01:20:57,746
Course, I favor cash.

1281
01:20:57,832 --> 01:21:01,083
Well, I was hoping to pay a
percentage of my crop yield.

1282
01:21:01,168 --> 01:21:04,136
That your big slave yonder?

1283
01:21:04,255 --> 01:21:05,921
Yep.

1284
01:21:06,006 --> 01:21:08,340
Mm, that Sambo's half the
down payment right here.

1285
01:21:08,426 --> 01:21:10,893
Oh, well, I'm gonna need Nate

1286
01:21:10,978 --> 01:21:13,062
to help me plough the field,
I mean, so's I can pay you.

1287
01:21:13,147 --> 01:21:17,299
But I was hoping to pay you
10% of my first year's yield,

1288
01:21:17,401 --> 01:21:20,402
then 20% every year thereafter.

1289
01:21:20,488 --> 01:21:21,970
I'll make an exception.

1290
01:21:22,073 --> 01:21:24,073
But don't tell nobody...

1291
01:21:24,158 --> 01:21:26,191
special circumstance, 'cause
I tend to favor a family man.

1292
01:21:26,277 --> 01:21:27,976
But at the very least, I'll need you to put

1293
01:21:28,079 --> 01:21:29,836
the negro up as collateral.

1294
01:21:30,448 --> 01:21:34,444
I can also allocate another
440 acres for ranching.

1295
01:21:35,269 --> 01:21:36,885
Ranching?

1296
01:21:36,988 --> 01:21:38,737
Comes from the Spaniards.

1297
01:21:38,856 --> 01:21:41,824
Cattle roam free, proliferate,
then sold on the hoof.

1298
01:21:41,909 --> 01:21:45,027
Mexicans been doing it for near 100 years.

1299
01:21:45,112 --> 01:21:46,245
No, I mean, farmland...

1300
01:21:46,364 --> 01:21:47,613
that's what I'm after.

1301
01:21:47,698 --> 01:21:49,582
Name?

1302
01:21:50,318 --> 01:21:53,936
Wykoff... James Wykoff.

1303
01:21:54,021 --> 01:21:58,657
Wykoff. What's your religion?

1304
01:21:58,776 --> 01:22:03,579
Well, now, my wife is
a hard-shelled Baptist.

1305
01:22:03,664 --> 01:22:07,666
Mexico only recognizes
those of Catholic faith.

1306
01:22:07,785 --> 01:22:09,818
Being a Catholic's not too bad;

1307
01:22:10,021 --> 01:22:12,721
you know, a priest instead of a preacher.

1308
01:22:12,807 --> 01:22:16,091
Well, then, we'll do right by him, Mister.

1309
01:22:16,193 --> 01:22:18,360
Signature.

1310
01:22:20,674 --> 01:22:21,985
- It's, uh...
- Yeah.

1311
01:22:32,743 --> 01:22:34,877
Yeah.

1312
01:22:34,962 --> 01:22:36,111
Welcome to Mexico.

1313
01:22:36,213 --> 01:22:37,663
- Thank you.
- [laughs]

1314
01:22:45,923 --> 01:22:48,807
[dramatic music]

1315
01:22:48,926 --> 01:22:56,849
♪ ♪

1316
01:23:07,328 --> 01:23:10,645
[flies buzzing]

1317
01:23:10,748 --> 01:23:12,882
(Wallace) My God, Jack.

1318
01:23:16,620 --> 01:23:18,153
Oh no.

1319
01:23:18,255 --> 01:23:26,261
♪ ♪

1320
01:23:45,232 --> 01:23:53,155
♪ ♪

1321
01:23:54,575 --> 01:23:56,708
[thunder rumbles in distance]

1322
01:24:13,010 --> 01:24:15,811
[mouthing]

1323
01:24:23,754 --> 01:24:25,972
Where you planning on heading now?

1324
01:24:29,343 --> 01:24:31,677
With you, I reckon.

1325
01:24:31,762 --> 01:24:36,265
Join up with the Texian army.

1326
01:24:36,350 --> 01:24:39,368
I figure it's what your brother
Samuel would want us to do.

1327
01:24:39,437 --> 01:24:42,605
[soft, pleasant music]

1328
01:24:42,690 --> 01:24:50,446
♪ ♪

1329
01:24:50,548 --> 01:24:54,533
(Wallace) I must say you're
looking mighty dignified.

1330
01:24:54,619 --> 01:24:58,587
Yeah, well, I'd sooner ride
on a burro than with an ass.

1331
01:24:58,673 --> 01:25:00,706
Smells a lot better too.

1332
01:25:00,791 --> 01:25:03,208
I will rectify the stink upon arrival

1333
01:25:03,294 --> 01:25:04,826
to Buckley's way station.

1334
01:25:04,929 --> 01:25:08,597
I can only hope, but I fear
that the ass will linger.

1335
01:25:08,683 --> 01:25:10,766
♪ ♪

1336
01:25:10,851 --> 01:25:12,885
[laughing]

1337
01:25:12,970 --> 01:25:15,771
(Wallace) You're riding
that thing pretty well.

1338
01:25:15,856 --> 01:25:21,527
(Baker) Remember that
the author of all this woe

1339
01:25:21,646 --> 01:25:24,313
is tyrant Santa Anna,

1340
01:25:24,398 --> 01:25:28,350
and Sam Houston does nothing.

1341
01:25:28,452 --> 01:25:31,453
(man) I know your families are suffering.

1342
01:25:31,539 --> 01:25:34,657
I know that I brought you here not to run,

1343
01:25:34,742 --> 01:25:36,575
but to fight...

1344
01:25:36,661 --> 01:25:38,460
to stand and fight!

1345
01:25:38,546 --> 01:25:40,329
(all) Stand and fight!

1346
01:25:40,431 --> 01:25:41,880
Stand and fight!

1347
01:25:41,999 --> 01:25:43,832
Stand and fight! Stand and fight!

1348
01:25:43,918 --> 01:25:49,304
(Baker) Now is the time to avenge
the blood of our fallen heroes!

1349
01:25:49,407 --> 01:25:53,642
Remember to nerve yourselves for battle

1350
01:25:53,728 --> 01:25:57,763
knowing that our cause is just,

1351
01:25:57,848 --> 01:26:01,266
and that our code words will be,

1352
01:26:01,352 --> 01:26:04,570
"Remember the Alamo!"

1353
01:26:04,849 --> 01:26:06,148
(all) Stand and fight!

1354
01:26:06,173 --> 01:26:08,090
Stand and fight! Stand and fight!

1355
01:26:08,175 --> 01:26:11,593
Patriots. Patriots, listen!

1356
01:26:11,679 --> 01:26:14,797
We must stand by General Houston.

1357
01:26:14,882 --> 01:26:19,601
General Houston needs to
stand his ground and fight!

1358
01:26:19,687 --> 01:26:22,337
He needs to stand and fight!

1359
01:26:22,820 --> 01:26:24,020
(all) Stand and fight!

1360
01:26:24,045 --> 01:26:25,378
Stand and fight! Stand and fight!

1361
01:26:25,403 --> 01:26:26,869
Stand and fight!

1362
01:26:26,894 --> 01:26:28,593
(man) I order you men to disperse now!

1363
01:26:28,679 --> 01:26:30,929
(all) Stand and fight! Stand and fight!

1364
01:26:31,015 --> 01:26:32,547
(man) Disperse!

1365
01:26:32,649 --> 01:26:33,648
(all) Stand and fight! Stand and fight!

1366
01:26:33,734 --> 01:26:35,100
Disperse now!

1367
01:26:35,185 --> 01:26:36,151
(all) Stand and fight!

1368
01:26:36,236 --> 01:26:37,269
(man) Now!

1369
01:26:40,057 --> 01:26:45,901
(Baker) Remember the next time
Sam Houston orders a grave dug...

1370
01:26:45,996 --> 01:26:49,664
- Make way.
- It will be his very own.

1371
01:26:56,223 --> 01:26:58,056
(Houston) Cold water
will cool that hot head.

1372
01:26:58,175 --> 01:27:01,009
Have you no shame, sir?

1373
01:27:01,094 --> 01:27:04,679
You can beat us, but you cannot silence us.

1374
01:27:06,600 --> 01:27:07,982
Stand and fight.

1375
01:27:08,068 --> 01:27:09,818
(all) Stand and fight!

1376
01:27:09,903 --> 01:27:12,437
Stand and fight! Stand and fight!

1377
01:27:12,522 --> 01:27:14,823
Stand and fight! Stand and fight!

1378
01:27:14,908 --> 01:27:16,157
[gunshot]

1379
01:27:19,062 --> 01:27:21,930
Y'all need to cool down,

1380
01:27:22,015 --> 01:27:24,299
'cause we's all that's left.

1381
01:27:24,401 --> 01:27:27,736
Colonel Fannin and his men are gone.

1382
01:27:27,821 --> 01:27:30,305
God damn it to hell.

1383
01:27:30,407 --> 01:27:34,075
Goliad is no more.

1384
01:27:34,161 --> 01:27:36,278
Fannin disobeyed ordered.

1385
01:27:36,363 --> 01:27:41,082
His army did not survive because of it.

1386
01:27:41,168 --> 01:27:43,668
Should we do the same...

1387
01:27:43,787 --> 01:27:46,421
fight each other,

1388
01:27:46,506 --> 01:27:48,206
disobey our General?

1389
01:27:51,962 --> 01:27:54,296
And you, General,

1390
01:27:54,381 --> 01:27:56,181
will you lead your men?

1391
01:28:00,103 --> 01:28:03,355
I feel your scorn,

1392
01:28:03,473 --> 01:28:06,775
and I know I'm the reason for your dissent

1393
01:28:06,860 --> 01:28:09,361
when our cause can least afford it.

1394
01:28:13,200 --> 01:28:16,701
I was broken when I came to Texas.

1395
01:28:16,820 --> 01:28:19,738
I failed at my marriage

1396
01:28:19,823 --> 01:28:23,325
and turned my back on
the people of Tennessee.

1397
01:28:23,410 --> 01:28:26,861
I took refuge among the Cherokee

1398
01:28:26,963 --> 01:28:30,999
and failed them too.

1399
01:28:31,084 --> 01:28:35,887
I disappointed my family...
tarnished their good name.

1400
01:28:36,006 --> 01:28:38,039
I will atone for all
that when my time comes,

1401
01:28:38,141 --> 01:28:40,392
but I am no longer that man,

1402
01:28:40,510 --> 01:28:43,061
and the reason is Texas.

1403
01:28:43,180 --> 01:28:44,429
My heart beats strong again.

1404
01:28:44,514 --> 01:28:49,217
My head is clear. I see
a future beckoning us.

1405
01:28:49,319 --> 01:28:53,154
I did not ask to be your general.

1406
01:28:53,240 --> 01:28:56,191
I was asked by our government to lead you.

1407
01:28:56,276 --> 01:29:00,895
Now, I ask you to follow me east

1408
01:29:00,997 --> 01:29:03,915
where I believe victory awaits us,

1409
01:29:04,034 --> 01:29:08,253
for God has willed that
no tyrant will ever rule.

1410
01:29:08,372 --> 01:29:11,956
Follow me a little longer
down this twisted, bloody road,

1411
01:29:12,042 --> 01:29:14,342
and I will prove it to you.

1412
01:29:17,814 --> 01:29:19,848
By God, I'll prove it.

1413
01:29:24,821 --> 01:29:27,956
[crying]

1414
01:29:39,203 --> 01:29:42,137
[somber music]

1415
01:29:42,239 --> 01:29:50,178
♪ ♪

1416
01:29:59,323 --> 01:30:02,624
Holy Father, please watch
over Truett and Yancey.

1417
01:30:02,726 --> 01:30:04,526
I miss them.

1418
01:30:05,929 --> 01:30:13,902
♪ ♪

1419
01:30:19,843 --> 01:30:21,477
[cries softly]

1420
01:30:30,432 --> 01:30:32,032
Come to relieve me, Tom?

1421
01:30:32,128 --> 01:30:33,595
It has been discussed.

1422
01:30:33,620 --> 01:30:36,011
Before we are outnumbered
why don't we attack?

1423
01:30:36,011 --> 01:30:39,489
Your insubordination
could have cost us dearly.

1424
01:30:39,543 --> 01:30:41,806
Death before betrayal.

1425
01:30:42,614 --> 01:30:47,622
The worst we must do lies yet
ahead, judge me as you will.

1426
01:30:47,647 --> 01:30:49,567
What do you need this for?

1427
01:30:50,512 --> 01:30:52,934
Let me introduce Daphne

1428
01:30:53,215 --> 01:30:56,457
and her equally pretty sister Penelope.

1429
01:30:56,512 --> 01:30:58,074
Alright then let's see how fast we can get

1430
01:30:58,074 --> 01:30:59,590
one of them sisters ready.

1431
01:30:59,690 --> 01:31:00,801
[BOOM]

1432
01:31:00,964 --> 01:31:02,231
There was a shooting.

1433
01:31:02,356 --> 01:31:05,673
And you gonna tell me you are
all just innocent bystanders?

1434
01:31:08,696 --> 01:31:10,801
Necessity requires your help.

1435
01:31:11,040 --> 01:31:12,282
Comanches.

1436
01:31:13,232 --> 01:31:14,727
We end it all now.

1437
01:31:14,783 --> 01:31:16,001
Shoot me first.

1438
01:31:16,026 --> 01:31:17,560
You don't think I will?

1439
01:31:17,585 --> 01:31:19,607
Tomorrow we march!

1440
